Republican strategy to resist Obama's re-election
Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth, arguing that cases of electoral fraud in the United States are more rare than deaths from lightning strikes.
In addition, Republican lawyers counted only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new trends will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
Unlike Canada, the U.S. states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
That is why most state governments since 2009 have enacted laws that complicate the process of registration or voting.
This phenomenon gained new momentum after the November 2010 election, which brought Republicans 675 new seats in 26 states.
As a result, in 2011 alone, 180 bills were passed restricting voting rights in 41 states.
New electoral laws require voters to show a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws shorten the period of early voting, abolish the right to register a voter on the day of expression of will and deprive citizens with criminal records of the right to vote.
Prior to the 2006 election, no state in the United States required voters to show a photo ID.
Indiana became the first state to introduce such a requirement.
The U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of the Indiana law in 2008.
The republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have initiated bills requiring voters to show photo IDs in 34 states.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have such a universal identity card as a health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of American citizens, that is, 21 million people who have reached the voting age, do not have an identity card with a photo issued by the government body of their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a document.
At the same time, the cost of obtaining the required identity card often exceeds one hundred dollars.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African-Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over the age of 65, and 20% of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
But that's not all.
Student voters who are believed to vote for Democratic candidates are not allowed in several states to use a photo ID issued by their school.
But the same states allow members of fishing and hunting clubs, who vote mainly for Republicans, to use certificates issued by these clubs to vote.
Until 2004, no state required proof of U.S. citizenship to vote.
This was the first time such a requirement was introduced in Arizona.
Since 2011, more than a dozen states have enacted laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are obviously aimed at limiting the voting of Latin Americans.
It is believed that two-thirds of Latin American voters vote in favor of the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers initiated laws in 2011 abolishing voter registration on voting day in eight states.
They also restricted the right of individuals or groups to assist those wishing to register.
This restriction did not go without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 elections, the voter registration campaign helped to list some 10 million citizens.
At the same time, measures taken since 2009 have led to a 17 per cent drop in the level of new voter registration in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers have enacted laws in five other states aimed at shortening the early voting period.
During the 2008 Florida general election, 33% of early voters were African-American, although the latter accounted for only 13% of the state's total voters.
The same thing happened with Latin Americans.
Representing only 11% of voters, they made up 24% of citizens who voted early.
Unlike the whites, who, forming 76% of the voters, among the early voters were only 46%.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters actively oppose the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills have been vetoed by Democratic governors.
The most controversial laws were suspended with the intervention of the United States Attorney General.
This has partially reduced the negative effects.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have enacted laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID card.
However, the new rules that have come into force will undoubtedly make it difficult to exercise the right to vote in the 2012 elections.
Critics from Democrats have condemned the bias of the laws that have been passed, seeing in them an obvious focus on influencing the results of the 2012 election in key states.
A 2011 report by the Brennan Center shows that states enacting these laws represent 171 of the 270 electoral college votes needed to win the presidential election.
It is too early to say with confidence that these legislative changes at the electoral system level will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential election.
Only one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
