The Higgs boson in detail
Last summer, a report that scientists may have been able to detect the Higgs boson caused a real stir – and not without reason.
It is believed that this boson explains the mass of all particles in the universe, neither much nor little.
Moreover, it is the last particle whose existence was predicted within the Standard Model—our best, or at least our least imperfect, description of the nature and behavior of matter—but which has not been previously discovered by experiment.
But physicists are not quite sure that we are talking about the Higgs boson.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we are dealing with a truly new particle and that it strongly resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, the new data presented this week at one major physical congress in Kyoto seems to confirm this, although for complete certainty some data is still not enough.
Let’s assume that we are talking about the Higgs boson, because the chances of making a mistake seem minimal, and let’s see what it means.
There is, in this world, one law absolutely inevitable, which states that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There is no way to circumvent this rule, do not even try too hard, otherwise you will harm yourself.
But although particle physics is a rather strange world, it turns out that it also has one law of a similar nature: the Pauli exclusion principle, which postulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" is, in general terms, in some of their characteristics.
Based on this, physicists divide particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find good citizens, called fermions, who reasonably obey the Pauli principle.
In the other, the bosons, a vile band of anarchists who have no respect for anything — at least this principle — are fussing, which means they can quietly be in the same place at the same time.
As reported by the site (by the way, quite unusual) Particle Adventure Berkeley Laboratory, these bosons are divided, in turn, into two groups: mesons, about which we will not talk here, and "particles of force", through which the main forces of nature are propagated and to which the Higgs boson belongs in some way.
These very bosons, it should be emphasized, are not all such exotic beings as one might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to one incredibly banal boson: the photon, or "particle of light", which is the "courier" of electromagnetic force.
In fact, when one particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it “disrupts” the electromagnetic field at that particular place, like a rock thrown into a pond.
From this "disorder" an electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared radiation, or ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing but a photon - and hence one of the bosons of the "power carriers".
A more stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, with the only difference that in order for this boson to appear, another field, the Higgs field, must be “broken”.
However, the Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, it is necessary to reach very, very high energies, as if it were a frozen pond, the surface of which could be shaken only by a very large stone.
That’s why a huge particle accelerator like the one operated at CERN – the Large Hadron Collider, which is a ring with a diameter of 27 km! – is needed to achieve such huge energies.
The electromagnetic field analogy is also useful for explaining the relationship between the Higgs boson and mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, interact, while others do not: a piece of paper, for example, will never stick on the refrigerator itself.
Similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that interact have mass, while others (like the photon, by the way) do not.
So, what “may bring” all this research, Ms. Plamondon asks?
In science, they are used to verify the correctness of the Standard Model (SM), and it also allows physicists to sense the discrepancy between the results of observations and the predictions of SM.
In addition, some of them are eager for such a discrepancy to be discovered, because the slightest discrepancy can open the door to "new physics" and shut some holes in the Model.
The latter, I must say, still has significant flaws, offering no explanation for gravity (oh!) or for dark matter, which forms about 80% of the universe (oh!).
But so far, no such discrepancies have been found in CERN.
Consequences
The benefits of these studies for the daily life of the average person are more difficult to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that there is none.
See: In the early 1960s, the pioneers of laser research in Bell’s labs could not have even guessed what kind of revolution their work would cause.
They envisioned their applications in science, but nothing more.
Indeed, the late physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Laboratories, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (previous ones were pulsed) in 1962, said that the laser was originally seen as a “laboratory gadget.”
Imagine...
And in addition, the application can be found for the toolkit accompanying the study.
For example, the same Billion Boyle during his optical research in 1969 developed a small light sensor.
This sensor, although it was not at all its original purpose, now serves as an "eye" for all digital cameras in the world and earned the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This, of course, does not mean that the work of the Large Hadron Collider will necessarily change our lives, but it only shows, in fact, that everything can be.
Palliative care is the best way to die... <0x7C> Debt
The commission for a dignified death in Quebec recently discussed the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate should resume soon, and at this time a bill is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this critical area.
"Debt" tried to take a closer look.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in Monterey.
Prostate cancer, destroying him from the inside, gave him a delay of two years.
"I was given five years, I lived seven," he says, between life and death, lying in bed at Victor-Gadbois's palliative care home in Beloye, where he arrived the day before.
“But it’s always a shock, it’s impossible to prepare for it,” he says.
The disease does its job: an incredible weakness that prevents you from going to the toilet on your own and even eating on your own.
Sitting at a table where there is an appetizing lunch, he gives up and agrees to be helped to eat.
He wakes up, even manages to smile, talk to strangers who work around him, bring him medicines, take him to the bathroom.
Courage before a normal death.
“My greatest desire to be cured of diarrhea is humiliating,” he admits.
A few hours later, the staff found a cure for this ailment.
“Throughout life, we are taught that a man should urinate standing,” says Pierre Broder, a psychologist at Victor-Gadbois.
Regression to the state of the child is an intolerable humiliation for some.
“It all depends on a person’s ability to accept decline,” he argues.
Since, according to many people involved in palliative care, important events occur even in the midst of this decline.
Patients who go to Victor-Gadbois palliative care are all cancer patients.
Forecasts give them a maximum of three months to live.
At this stage, a team of doctors and nurses no longer provide a care called “treatment.”
Ms. A., 89, is most afraid of dying “with consciousness from suffocation.”
But the disease allowed me to know my children.
“I have good kids,” she adds.
“I don’t want anything else in life,” she says before allowing her to put on a breathing mask.
She is still waiting in the coming days for the last visit of her son, who came from Italy.
The Victor-Gadbois shelter provides body care and nutritional assistance with the help of a group of volunteers.
This is the palliative care that remains when nothing else can be done.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, for every 11,700 inhabitants, there is one place in palliative care facilities.
That's very little, given that sooner or later we're all going to die.
Here life continues in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christian Martel, one of the doctors of the shelter.
Whether it is physical, emotional or mental comfort.
We'll give the dying man a mouth rinse of brandy or pepsi, depending on what he asks.
We no longer force diabetics to control their sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night we brought beer to Mr. H., who died tonight.
In the morning, his son drank this beer at the feet of the deceased.
“We help our loved ones as well as our patients,” says Natalie Savar, director of care.
At Victor-Gadbois, no day is like the previous.
Next to a 93-year-old man who enjoys his last meeting with his family in the yard, sitting on his pillows during a toast in his honor, tragically dies a young man 36 years old, surrounded by his parents, wife and two young children and tried everything to survive.
“In the last six months, three to five beds have always been occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45,” says Dr. Christian Martel.
53% of patients admitted to the Victor-Gadbois shelter come from home, and 47% from the hospital.
The problem of access to palliative care
It is believed that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, to care that is provided to alleviate the suffering of patients who have entered the final stage of their lives, whether at home, in a hospital or in a shelter.
And some institutions, such as the Victor-Gadbois Shelter and the Greater Montreal Palliative Care Society, specialize more or less exclusively in caring for cancer patients.
It is this large gap in Quebec’s health care system that makes many palliative care practitioners fear the passage of a law legalizing euthanasia and assisting suicide.
Since October, a manifesto has been circulating, signed by the Palliative Care luminaries, Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapuant, and testifying to their disagreement with such an initiative.
According to Dr Christian Martel, Quebec’s health care system is insufficient to ensure the right to high-quality palliative care before the transition to euthanasia is allowed.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who spent 14 days in the ambulance ward, in terrible pain, and no one took the necessary measures to relieve them.
I'm afraid that patients only want to die because they don't receive adequate care.
At the same time, many oncologists are trying to save patients until the last day, despite pessimistic forecasts.
Hopes for Ellen Richard’s survival were already minimal when she stopped exhausting chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she told me that she regretted that I was stopping the fight.
She told me that my days were numbered.
There is no all-powerful care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask for death are thanked by the medical staff for not fulfilling their request, after a palliative care team relieves their pain.
However, it should be noted that palliative care is not absolutely omnipotent in the fight against pain.
According to Elsie Monroe, director of palliative care at the Palliative Care Society of Greater Montreal, patients are not susceptible to painkillers in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, in which the patient sleeps until the moment of his death, either from time to time or permanently.
We can no longer pretend that we do not know about these sufferings.
More and more often, patients who fail to relieve pain will be able to access palliative sedation.
Patients who suffer from pain always say the same phrase: “I want to die”.
But it doesn’t necessarily mean “I want to be euthanized,” it means “I want to feel better.”
