Pay and sell without the help of banks - with Bitcoin
The complete opposite of the current money exchange based on central banks, numbered transactions between the receiving parties with commission fees for their processing.
In addition, as often happens with these technologies, a political vision is evident: the belief that the current monetary system, consisting of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but convertible to dollars, euros...) and a secure exchange protocol like BitTorrent, which allows file sharing between participants of the same level.
About 200,000 transactions have already been registered with 15,000 computers on the network.
Several thousand sites accept bitcoins for donations or as a means of payment.
Bitcoin’s exchange rate, which peaked at $30 (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>23) in June 2011, fell to $2 five months later before returning to about $10 today (the rates are listed on bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing special compared to the global exchange of real money or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) in its report on the virtual currency, published in October, was interested in this system.
He describes bitcoin as “the most successful virtual currency,” “competing with the dollar or the euro,” and “similar to conventional currencies.”
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies as "credits" used to promote a video game, which are earned during the game or which can be bought (and sometimes exchanged).
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
But exchange operations are always controlled and processed by a central authority.
In Bitcoin, all nodes of the network are simultaneously book holders, auditors, currency issuers, buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two email addresses, much like an email.
Only for each new payment can the user choose a different address, thus ensuring anonymity.
The set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically, using a double-key encryption system.
The network can also verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is possible to verify that the bitcoins used in the transaction do exist in a public ledger sent across the network.
The key step is to register a new transaction in this book.
It goes through solving a mathematical problem sent to computers, which, like a temporary central bank, gets the privilege of adding this new line.
This is the hashing phase of a file, that is, the conversion of a large file into a digital signature, short and unique.
Computers "take" a new transaction and add a number to it before "hashing" them all together.
The goal is to find a number that will give a unique digital signature (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, other nodes easily check that it is correct.
The transaction is thus inextricably linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification will alter the digital signature.
If, for the purpose of deception, a user would very quickly (in less than ten minutes) want to pay twice with the same money, only one of these two transactions would be confirmed by the network - and the other would remain unconfirmed, since they have different electronic signatures.
The computer that solves the problem receives 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, the prize is regularly split in half, probably until the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible by one hundred millionth, which leaves a reserve.
The complexity of the task also increases with the increase in computing power.
The life of the network has already experienced ups and downs.
Sites providing Bitcoin services have been attacked, and bitcoins have been stolen from reserves.
“The defect used does not concern the protocol itself,” says Pierre Noise, who recently launched Paymium, a real-money payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reported on the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this disadvantage.
Big players like Wikipedia refuse to accept donations of this kind.
Others, such as the WordPress blogging platform, allow them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the ledger and found that almost 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
"Giant Sales" was announced in November.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” rejoices Jon Holmqvist, who works at Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noise, another author of the manual on this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as an operating network.
Its system, Paytunia, is the equivalent of a credit card (in real money) or contactless payment via a mobile phone, but it uses Bitcoin to verify transactions, making it cheaper.
The owner has better control over his personal data and can thus be anonymous.
The system is simple to implement for entrepreneurs who do not need to install new devices or software.
It is enough to provide an address that can be “photographed and recognized” by the phone, Pierre Noise clarifies, assuring that he already has thousands of users.
There is a general tendency to revise hierarchical systems in favor of more horizontal ones.
“Bitcoin will take some time to establish itself, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicts.
The ECB’s report proposes, incidentally, to review the various risks considered heightened today if the system succeeds.
