The Difficult Birth of the Egyptian Constitution
This is a new risky move by President Mohamed Morsi.
While Egypt is divided more than ever, on the issue of the constitutional declaration, which temporarily gives it extraordinary powers, he decided to play in the bank.
Surprising everyone, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on the final text the next day.
Exactly a week ago, the head of state granted the Assembly two additional months to complete the work.
Soon, for two years now, Egypt is relying on a provisional text that has been amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal controversy.
This new initiative only strengthened the division of the country.
According to his opponents, the President persists in his “autocratic delusion”, continuing to “violate this word” and “trample on the law”.
His followers in the camp believe that this is a way to end the institutional and political crisis by speeding up the transition process.
The referendum must be held within 15 days.
A very short period of time, which causes the Brothers to abandon the intention of explaining to the Egyptians the text, article by article.
For the president, it is also a way to restore public and democratic legitimacy, while discontent rages across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote positively, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
The call for an expedited vote resembles an ultimatum to the Egyptian people: “Either you vote for my text, or I retain my extraordinary powers,” which is supposed to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
In this strange atmosphere, 85 members of the Constituent Assembly, mostly Islamists, voted for the text yesterday.
Most liberals did not respond to the challenge.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they slammed the door, feeling unable to convey their opinion.
Representatives of human rights defenders, religious minorities or civil society did the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 people, spare participants, were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Not surprisingly, in most cases, the articles were voted on unanimously.
The commentators, by the way, were amused by the fact that one of the few disagreements of the day arose around ... the time for prayer, as some members of the committee felt that the clock of the Constituent Assembly had been set wrong.
The text, which was voted on yesterday, consists of 234 articles.
The object of general attention, article 2 ultimately remained identical to the article of the 1971 Constitution, which states that “the principles of Shariah are the main source of law”.
The Salafist parties, for whom the introduction of Islamic law is one of the basic requirements, hoped to replace the "principles" with "rules", which would allow for their stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a testament to their goodwill and respect for other members of Egyptian society.
“Hypocrisy,” respond the liberals, who see it as PR.
Because, in their opinion, the Islamization of the Constitution occurs through other articles.
They refer in particular to article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, particularly with regard to the verification of compliance with Sharia law.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pomier, this is alarming, because "the people called to make decisions are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy."
We can see the birth of theocracy.”
Many liberals are also excited by the fact that the university’s next rector appears to be far less moderate than the current one.
“At the moment, there is no specific religious interference.
With this constitution, we remain within the framework of civil law.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not ulemas, but people with university degrees, some trained in the French system," says Alexis Bloe, who is preparing a dissertation on Egypt's constitutional transition.
But he admits that "ambiguity may arise around Article 220, since the terms used in it are borrowed from religious vocabulary.
This applies in particular to the fiqh [Islamic jurisprudence].
And in the future, the question may arise as to how civil judges are competent to rule on this.”
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is criticized because it gives broad powers to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood claims that they are significantly reduced compared to what they were under the old regime.
Another point of contention: the powers of the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the defense budget will not be considered in Parliament, but in the National Defense Council.
There will also be no ban on the trial of civilians in military courts, despite requests from human rights associations.
The latter also expressed concern about the text, which they consider to be detrimental to freedom.
Responsibility for blasphemy remains, and insults are now prohibited, which can have serious consequences for freedom of speech, and especially for freedom of the press.
In addition, none of the articles talks about the protection of women anymore, emphasizes Heba Moraef, of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive aspect was the prohibition of torture in article 36.
A word that did not appear in the previous Constitution.
