"This is Venus and Mars," said Vladimir Surdin, senior researcher at the State Astronomical Institute named after P.K. Sternberg (GAISh).
But if the conditions on Mars are more suitable for life, then on the surface of Venus - temperatures of 500 degrees.
You can only live at high altitude or in the orbit of Venus... in space.
Approach to the issues of reproduction in space began with the flora.
Half a century ago, experiments on plants were conducted.
Four generations of peas grown in orbit were no different from their terrestrial varieties.
Then - the introduction into orbit of insects, tiny fruit flies - drosophila.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent to space to test how the embryo develops in weightlessness.
We get an absolutely normal chick at the exit.
And then the problem begins.
“The problem is that this chick has to find support, he has to stand on his feet and start moving,” explains Vladimir Sychev, head of the laboratory of the Institute of Medical and Biological Problems (IMBP) of the Russian Academy of Sciences.
Unable to find support, the chicks roared indiscriminately.
And after 10 hours, the newborns had a complete atrophy of instincts.
The chicks did not respond to light and sound.
And the trouble was that after four days they just died.
"And twice we hatched chicks, then refused, because it is simply impossible to work with them there," Vladimir Sychev states the failure of the experiment with chicks in space.
The last time a biological "minikovich" flew into orbit with animals was 16 years ago.
In the spring of 2013, the experiments will continue.
However, on the biosatellite "Bion" will be only same-sex individuals.
There was an experiment with rats that were sent into space already with a fetus.
In principle, there was nothing supernatural there.
"It was just on biosputniks, but again - this is a single experiment, and such research should be carried out," - said Vladimir Sychev.
After landing, space rats had offspring.
