Poland and Space.
Last week, at the European Space Agency ministerial meeting, Poland was accepted by the 20th member of the European Space Agency as the second country from the former Eastern Bloc countries (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 September 2008).
Poland began working closely with ESA in 1994 and during the following years took an active part in a number of ESA projects.
But the path to space Poland began much earlier.
Even before World War II, Polish enthusiasts were engaged in space flights, but this was not always met with understanding.
Let me recall, for example, the lecture of A. Sternfeld, who on December 6, 1933 presented at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory ideas from his groundbreaking work "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
The ideas of the young engineer (1905) left the audience indifferent, after several years Sternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomsky was interested in his work.
In 1934, in France, Sternfeld won the Robert Esno-Peltry and André Louis Hirsch Awards for "Introduction to Space."
Dr. Jan Gadomsky (1899-1966), mentioned above, later became a great propagandist of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a number of books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky became a world-renowned space propagandist, and his contribution was appreciated, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the moon was named in his honor.
Already in 1925, a railway train equipped with a rocket engine was built in Poland.
Unfortunately, the author of this idea remained unknown, as well as the details of the project.
It is not even clear whether a rocket had to be used to accelerate or brake the truck.
Information about this train is known only from the press of that era.
Since 1933, Polish artillery began to think about missile arrows.
The research was carried out by the Arms Technology Section in cooperation with Professors Mieczys<0xC5><0x82>aw Wolfke and Gustav Mokrzycki.
From the surviving materials it is clear that the research has reached the stage of practical testing.
But with the arrival of the German troops, work was interrupted.
In 1937, the idea of a photoelectric fighter missile, proposed by engineer Rogozinsky, appeared in the specialized press, and the following year the work "Air torpedo rocket and aviation bomb missile" by the author Lelyva-Khivlozky was published.
Both projects were developed for the military use of rocket engines.
Before the war, all projects for the military use of missiles were carried out by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczyskowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all the work.
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the work ended due to the outbreak of the war.
The next scientific work devoted to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The society was first mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the journal Problems, which published four voluminous articles on astronautics.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotovich proposed to organize a society that would be engaged in cosmonautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were already gaining momentum, and it was clear that space exploration was a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Society of Astronautics (POA) has been trying to join the International Astronautics Federation (founded in 1951), and already in the fall, the PAA became a full member of it.
The following year, the first chairman of the POA, Kazimierz Zarankevich (1902-1959), became deputy chairman of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He remained in this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, POA has made a significant contribution to the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket RM (Rakeeta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first type RM-1 was completed in 1957, and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket, able to overcome the distance of 1800 m, was about 80 cm long, and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959, tests of the two-stage RM-2 missile were conducted in the Bled wasteland.
This rocket was about 1.4 m long, and its weight was about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the rocket was already able to engage in real scientific work - the RM-34 missile could overcome 14.5 km, and its task was to observe the high-altitude wind.
But in 1962, further development was suspended.
The successor to the first RM-type missiles was the Meteor-1 missile, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was conceived as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm, and the initial weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (designated Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed in the size of the camera for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1B - 0.34 liters, and Meteor-1S - 0.62 liters.
The maximum range for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was developed at the Aviation Institute, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket with a launch weight of 380 kg was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
Then were built versions of Meteor-2H and Meteor-3.
It is also worth mentioning the accession of Poland to the COSPAR (Space Research Committee) in 1960 and the establishment of the COSPAR National Committee two years later.
In addition, as part of the Intercosmos program, Poland participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslav Germaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
Abolishing the law on public works is not a solution to the problem.
Last week, the Constitutional Court overturned the law on public works.
The decision sparked a heated debate in the community.
Undoubtedly, it will be interesting to look at this issue from a broader point of view.
Liberal economic systems in the EU, as well as in a globalized world, are based on the principle of multiple, unregulated economic competition.
In essence, this means that individual economic subdivisions, national economic systems, are in constant conflict with each other.
This is due to the principle of free trade and the free, unrestricted movement of private capital along with unbridled financial speculation.
As a result of a significant difference in the cost of labor (wages) there is a price tension.
Under this concept it is necessary to understand the state when the producer, by means of the delivery of cheap goods, tries to stand in economic competition by "beating down" the value of the competitor in order to take away most of the market and thus increase his own income.
On a massive scale, this means for most entrepreneurs either moving production abroad, or cheap purchases abroad, or disappearing. As a result, unemployment increases in those countries where the cost of labor, compared to others, is high.
Since private capital bears no social responsibility, including for the unemployment it produces, the inevitable expenditure of the state on social needs increases.
In general, the situation increases the reluctance of entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thereby compensate for the social and economic damage they cause in their pursuit of profit.
The situation is so well known that there is no need to provide specific statistics.
The unscrupulous methods of private capital create situations at the level of the economies of individual states when the governments of countries are forced to compete with each other in order to artificially reduce the social level of their population in order to attract foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments give their own populations to private capital despite social decline.
This is reflected primarily in the changes in the current legislation.
The goal is to economically force its people to submit to the dictates of private capital, especially in the field of wages.
It acts as a system of economic coercion in the case of long-term unemployment and at the same time serves as a tool for reducing the rights of workers in the field of labor legislation.
As a result, the level of poverty increases, and at the same time the gap between the poor and the rich.
In Germany, for several years, there has been a social distribution of food to the poor, who are unable to feed themselves by their own labor.
The number of these people is already approaching a million.
As part of improving the competitiveness of the German economy, there are constantly cases when employed people receive such a salary that the state must pay them extra so that they get a living wage.
Such a scandal became known to the public and in the case of additional employees of the Bundestag.
Economic measures in virtually all southern EU states undoubtedly lead to the same situation in which people under the pressure of a catastrophic decline in social status are forced either to emigrate, as it was in the 19th century, or to exist for a miserable wage in the backyard of society in the hope that private investment capital will one day come to the country.
But the question is, where will it come from?
If capital comes from other EU countries, then poverty will move from one country to another, or it will not come at all, since Chinese, Indian, Brazilian, Turk, Moroccan, Egyptian, African still work for a share of European wages.
This applies to all of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media argue that the state cannot participate in the capital of its own economy, that a managed economy leads to economic catastrophe.
Private capital insists that the state should not intervene in the economy.
Next, the question must be answered whether private capital, now practically managing politics and the entire state, does not act for its own selfish purposes?
The unambiguous answer is yes.
The proof is the existence of almost omnipotent and ubiquitous lobbies in all states.
As a result, we have a hopeless situation, manifested in corruption, ensuring mutual benefits, in legislation, where almost everything deserves punishment, but is not a crime.
In Germany, the situation is such that state ministries, due to lack of funds, entrust the drafting of bills to private law firms that are closely related to industry.
The bills are then approved by the Bundestag.
All power comes not from the people, as the constitution of the Western type says, but from financially powerful groups that prefer their own interests.
It is obvious that liberal democracy is now quickly finding itself in such a situation, as described by Appian in The Crisis of the Roman Empire in the Days of Caesar and Pompey: "The state has long been disintegrating, and the agencies are engaged in violence.
Bribes, the illegal receipt of graces with stones and swords.
Bribery and corruption flourished without any prohibitions, and the people went to the elections with a pre-sold vote"""...decent people did not run for the post of ruler at all, in the end, one day the state for eight months was left without a consul.". .. "Having seriously started to talk about what the only salvation in this terrible situation would be the impala, but the impala became the autocracy, and the need to choose an energetic man ".
As in ancient times, in modern society, its own reckless interests prevail without taking into account the public interest.
Private capital is no longer intrinsically intended for public use.
The present result is no different from the past: the unprecedented decline of the elite without any effort to carry out reforms of a deeper nature.
So the reason for the emergence of fascist and communist regimes we must look for in the reckless liberalization of economic systems of the 19th and 20th centuries.
To date, the absence of these regimes and the existence of a liberal-type democracy can be perceived as a certain pause, after which the next round is expected.
First of all, it is tragic that the current elite completely ignores the consequences of the hundreds of thousands of victims in the future, the humanitarian and social catastrophes that we are already witnessing, along with crimes against humanity, as we know it from old and new history.
The repeal of the law on public works is not a solution, or at least not permanently.
Under the pressure of competition at both the international and national and European levels, the Government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to further reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is therefore systemic.
The solution is targeted political and social reforms that will strengthen the share of the state in the economy, strengthen the role of citizens in the government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society in favor of the state.
