"Operation Argo": When it's worse, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of Islamist students seized the U.S. embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the ousted Shah Mohammed Reza Pahlavi, who had fled after the revolution to the United States, which had been the patron of his regime for decades.
For the US administration, the situation was not expected to be a positive outcome - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, because this could fundamentally undermine the confidence of allies in other countries.
However, it was not able to achieve the release of hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was later amplified by an unsuccessful attempt to free the hostages by force.
The detained diplomats were finally released after 444 days of negotiations mediated by the Algerian government.
Their fate sparked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iran sentiment at home.
The defeat in Iran greatly contributed to Jimmy Carter's defeat in the 1980 presidential election, which culminated in the election of Ronald Reagan.
The film, directed by actor Ben Affleck, “Operation Argo” describes one of the episodes of that story that brought America small victories.
Shortly before the occupation of the embassy, six workers managed to escape.
After difficult twists and turns, they ended their journey at the residence of the Embassy of Canada.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to take them out of Iran, while helping an extravagant cover legend, according to which they traveled on Canadian passports as members of the crew, looking for a place in the country to shoot a sci-fi epic.
Combination of genres
The plan, invented by evacuation expert Tony Mendes, demanded Hollywood’s cooperation.
In order for the legend to be credible, specialized magazines wrote about the film project, press conferences were held, the fictional production company had a real office.
Details of the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film is based on the memoirs of Tony Mendes.
Affleck’s film is a special combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a real political thriller, the so-called "cinema film", a story of a successful venture, a scam - an example can be a number of films about Ocean's friends.
The moods are constantly changing in the film - on the one hand, documentary scenes from Tehran (the credits show iconic historical photos of events and how the same situations were demonstrated in the film - there are no big differences in this).
On the other hand, lighter Hollywood passages intersecting with irony and moderate exaggeration.
And then scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in costumes discuss the situation at the negotiating tables, on the stairs of the institutions, on the phone ...
Ben Affleck did a great job of restarting his career.
From a ridiculed actor, he became a respected director, and his play ceased to be an object of ridicule.
"Operation Argo" is his third feature-length film, after the dark detective "Goodbye, Baby, Goodbye" (2007) and the thriller "The City" (2010).
At the same time, this is the first Affleck film that is not filmed in the director’s hometown of Boston.
The feeling of the atmosphere of the place at the same time refers to the qualities that elevated the earlier films of the director above the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck shows it at Argo, where Tehran plays Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place on the streets, in the reconstruction of real events - the opening scenes of the fall of the embassy impress with their clarity, which also conveys the emotions of confusion and unpredictability that arise when somewhere the story suddenly changes.
Affleck and his colleagues achieve a similar effect in fictional scenes (fake headquarters at the Tehran bazaar).
Too many processes in too many places.
The director had to deal with the fact that the narrative does not imply a lot of exciting scenes of cinematic significance.
He works quite successfully with this few, sometimes he thinks something out - it all comes out not so elegantly (the scene in which a phone call in America prevents an impending crisis at the airport of Tehran, and chasing on the runway looks rather far-fetched).
The disadvantage of Argo is the distraction associated with the need to show too many events in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman in the role of Hollywood colleagues are really very charming, but their characters would deserve more space, and they are not the only ones in the film.
The film lacks a bit of drama, it is a film that can be watched with moderate interest, judging the staging and retro-style, recreating the thrillers of the seventies.
But it's hard to capture.
However, this is enough to remind one, still in a certain sense of living history, as well as to testify to how exaggerated are the notions of omnipotent and omniscient intelligence services.
Rules for inflating balloons, bananas and circus
The portal www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which annually conducts a survey on the most absurd banking fees, has now decided to announce a competition for the "most absurd regulation or project from the EU workshop".
“We were prompted to this latest event, in which the EU plans to adopt a 40 percent quota for women in the administration of large European companies,” said Patrick Nager, the organizer of the survey.
Among the absurdities already put forward for the nomination is the recent decision of the European Court of Justice to unify the rates of insurance premiums for men and women.
So far, women have had life insurance benefits because they are objectively less at risk for insurance companies.
“Further incredible ideas from the EU workshop people can put forward for the competition before the end of this year.
The vote itself will take place until the end of February 2013," Nager said.
Controversial EU regulations include, for example, the mandatory addition of biocomponents to fuels, which as a result harms nature, as well as a ban on the use of reliable mercury thermometers just because they contain relatively small amounts of dangerous substances, or a directive on the size of the cage for hens, as a result of which eggs have significantly increased in price this year.
Also criticized was the de facto ban on the use of the term "sandwich oil" or the withdrawal from the sale of classic light bulbs.
High-quality bananas should be 14 centimeters long.
The pan-European apparatus often makes decisions under the pressure of a particular trade or industrial lobby, whose positions in Brussels are usually defended by a state or a group of states (thus, the Czech Republic now even defends the demands of its banks under the threat of veto).
The interests of the lobby are as follows: for example, bananas of the highest quality in the European Union had to reach a length of 14 cm and did not dare to show "abnormal curvature".
At the same time, the European Commission was justified by the fact that it only harmonises existing disparate national rules that complicated trade.
The EU, despite the resistance of some states, has still softened standards on fruit and vegetables, citing the fact that existing directives will lead to the waste of products.
Last year’s EU regulation, according to which sales of balloons must be provided with a warning that children under the age of eight can not inflate them without the supervision of adults, can be a candidate for winning in the survey.
The EU has turned to American studies, according to which balloons when playing are a potential cause of death of children by suffocation.
Such a restriction now applies to children under the age of 14, who are prohibited from blowing into fair dummies.
Funny ideas are born at home.
Quite absurd is the rule concerning the European officials themselves: anyone who has any official position in the EU, given the sensitivity of the topic for Greece, can not use the name of Macedonia, but should instead say "FYROM" (the former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
Bankovnípoplatky.com, in cooperation with the liberal economists’ association “Laissez Faire”, proposed for the vote, in addition to several of the above-mentioned absurd rules, for example, the EU rule on the volume of food stocks in the territory of a member state.
The EU has set the maximum amount of food stocks that can be on the territory of the Czech Republic on the date of its accession to the European Union.
Subsequently, the Czech Republic exceeded, for example, the established volumes of canned mushrooms, for which it was threatened with a large fine.
The organizers of the questionnaire were also interested in the idea of paying some countries for not having a sea, and the idea of granting subsidies for applying for subsidies.
But these ideas originated in Prague, not in Brussels.
“We are at a disadvantage because we have no sea.
We will ask the European Union for compensation," then-Agriculture Minister Yaroslav Palas (ChSDP) said in the autumn of 2004.
As an argument, he pointed out that the country had a high crop of grain and, as a result of the so-called intervention purchases, the State had full stockpiles of stocks that needed to be taken out.
For the fact that the Czech Republic is far from the ports, the EU, according to the Palace, had to pay us hundreds of millions of euros.
As a result, the European Commission went to the Czech Republic by organizing a tender for the purchase of grain from landlocked countries.
Subsidies for the grant were offered to the villages by the Ministry of Regional Development, headed by Minister Pavel Nemec (US-DEU), in particular, such subsidies were to be used to prepare an application for subsidies from Brussels.
EU: Weird orders are an exception
Although the regulations in the member states are easily criticized, the EU’s efforts to regulate, as well as to improve the functioning and development of the European Union, according to many experts, are rather worthy of recognition.
A serious problem, according to experts, is drawing on EU subsidies for projects that do not even have a hint of anything in common with the deepening of European integration, but which Member States have achieved when discussing the budget.
It is also emotion among Czechs that, as in other EU countries, the Czech Republic should fight in Brussels for the right to specific identification of its traditional products, and it does not always win in this competition.
Although the Czechs, after six years of fighting with the Germans and Austrians, retained the name "Olomouc cheeses", but "Tuzem rum", whose traditions in our country go back to the 19th century, our manufacturers had to rename it "Tuzemak".
Rum can only be called products from cane distillate, and not from sugar beet.
In the official list of registered products of the EU, along with the world-famous cheeses "feta" and "gorgondzola", marzipan from German Lübeck or Parma ham, were already, for example, Karlovy Vary biscuits, Pogorzelick and Tr<0xC5><0xA1>ebo<0xC5><0x88> carp and <0xC5><0xBD>atec hops.
Also, the EU trademark can be proud of Pardubice gingerbread and Gorzic tubes.
