MVRDV architects prove that real adventures are not only in the imagination - on the example of Speikenisse and his newly built Book Mountain - 2 photos
“To me, this building looks fun, it looks futuristic, finally we can see something interesting again,” says Lisette Verheig, walking by the side of the road.
Stefan Spermon, an IT specialist at a large company nearby, said: “No, this building is really beautiful.”
But I ask myself: why do we need another library today?
Everyone has the Internet, iPad and e-books.
Nowadays, no one volunteers to go to such old-fashioned libraries, right?
Speikenisse, a little-known sleeping town near Rotterdam, holds an unusual record.
Its population of 80,000 people has the lowest level of education in the Netherlands.
To combat this annoying circumstance a few years ago, it was decided to contribute to general education and build seven fictional bridges, which are depicted on euro banknotes, in the form of picturesquely painted miniatures of reinforced concrete.
The success of this educational initiative was modest.
And then the fathers of the city realized that they had only one chance to overcome the statistics: to build a library here!
Vinnie Maas of the Rotterdam architectural bureau MVRDV, a master of bold bar charts and author of witty, sometimes even cynical buildings, took the task with his usual serenity and appeared at a competitive audition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a smile on his face.
And while the jury members looked around in confusion and shrugged their shoulders, the daring Maas folded from his original gift a pyramid in size and concluded his speech in defense of his project with the following words: "Dear citizens!"
Here it is, my suggestion: "Book Mountain" in Speikenissa, the so-called Buchenberg!
Nine years later, this 30-million-euro mountain has grown.
It is part of a revitalization project that also includes an underground garage, a supermarket, a post office and several adjacent residential buildings and townhouses for a total of 50 apartments.
In early November, Book Mountain was awarded the second prize of the contest "Best Library of the Netherlands 2012".
The project also participates in the national Dutch competition of wooden structures in 2012.
Thus, a faceless suburb, which previously could offer nothing but a postmodern pedestrian zone and a surprisingly ugly town hall, the white facades of which suggest a dairy, became richer on one modern work of architecture.
But most importantly - in Speikenissa appeared the first in the history of this town public cultural building.
The Long Road to the Book
The first impression: a book Eldorado under the cheese cap.
There is only one elevator that passes in the center of the mountain range, because true fans of architecture and reading will prefer to explore this area on foot.
Glazed on all sides, the room is bright and easily visible, the floors of annealed bricks and elegant street lights unmistakably create the feeling of a public city square.
The urban environment is perfectly recreated.
The look involuntarily looks for benches, dogs and boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere - books, books, books.
"Usually, bookshelves stand along the facades, and in the middle there is a large dark hall, usually uncomfortable and faceless," says Vini Maas.
We put the classic configuration of space on its head and pulled the reading area from the inside out.
The inner space of the book mountain is skillfully used: in the center there are offices, an Internet library, a chess club, an environmental center and technical premises.
Particularly delighted are black bookshelves, which serve as decoration of walls, then parapets, then stair railings.
Their appearance, texture and smell are unusual.
Even sophisticated architects and engineers are lost in guessing what this unknown material is.
“We were keen to work with secondary materials,” explains Jop Trauborst, project manager representing the Speikenisse community, in line with the standard’s requirements.
And one day, at an agrarian enterprise in Friesland, we met a suitable by-product of agriculture.
For many years, in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands, an artificial fibrous material of millimeter thickness is used as a substrate for the roots.
It is cheap and saves time.
Thin textiles serve one or two seasons, after which it can be thrown away.
For the library, this canvas – for the first time in such volumes – was compressed in a panel four centimeters thick.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called landbauplastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous, durable material, smelling a bit like a new car and a little sneakers.
There are 105 steps to the top.
Anyone who crosses a path almost 500 meters long will be rewarded in a literary café not only with fantastic views of the city, but also with Dutch croquets and tree ficuses in pots.
They care about the atmosphere, and above all about the proper humidity of the air on the literary mountain.
The cost of a new soul
“It’s hard to believe, but this building, despite the many glass surfaces, is an exemplary project in terms of ecology,” says Trouborst.
For its heating and cooling, the heat of the earth is used.
Although the Book Mountain stands under a glass cap, even on clear days the sun gets inside only for a short time.
Wide farms of glued wood, located perpendicular to the glass facade, give shade and take on most of the sun's rays.
The climate in the room is very pleasant.
The remaining protection is provided by fully automatic roller blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the above-mentioned IT skeptic, has already visited the new library.
Lisette Verheig was already here.
Cynthia Bogard, a professor of traditional Chinese medicine, called Buchenberg “the soul of Speikenisse that has long been missing.”
Reason: A few weeks before the opening, each resident received an invitation to donate one book from his own collection.
These books were supposed to occupy empty spaces on the shelves of the not yet fully staffed library - at that time there were 70,000 books in it.
The idea worked.
The shelves are upstairs.
“There is nothing worse than a half-empty library,” says architect Vini Maas.
“I think that thanks to our invitation, every resident is now somehow connected to this new home.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's just for decoration.
Thus, MVRDV managed to solve the royal task, which in professional jargon is called identity creation.
Speikenisse wrote his literary history.
And let them be very young and uneducated.
This is only the starting point for identity building.
Szabo: "Germans should play a more important role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the recognition of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on U.S.-Europe relations, Berlin is balancing on a narrow diplomatic path.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany first made it clear that it would vote against the Palestinians’ application for observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
Why? Hmm?
Szabo: Germany does not support Israeli actions in Gaza.
Germany now needs to be cautious about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I believe that she does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained in the vote on the introduction of a no-fly zone.
In the end, NATO made the offer.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yes, it is.
The fact is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, namely moving from the policy, which, so to speak, was managed by the United States, to the actual German foreign policy.
In addition, the situation is complicated by the fact that the Europeans do not have a coherent single policy.
Once again, the Germans find themselves between the two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe that so far they are only grasping their role, but are on the way to a “more normal” foreign policy.
The kind of foreign policy that France or Britain pursues.
What exactly does “normal” foreign policy mean from the German point of view?
It is a willingness to take a position in their national interests, independent of the position of the United States or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policy, that is, on exports and ties with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany’s economic interests are largely different from those of other major states, and Germany must therefore defend its own interests.
Did these economic interests influence the position in the Middle East conflict and the UN vote?
First, Germany has major markets in the Middle East, particularly in the Gulf states.
Therefore, it needs to be careful not to offend the public and the elites in the Arab countries.
Either way, it plays a role.
But I wouldn’t give it too much importance, it’s not a completely one-sided relationship.
But in any case, it plays an important role in the calculations of the Germans.
Has Germany harmed its relations with the US by abstaining from making important decisions such as the Palestinian vote?
I am sure that in Europe, and even in the United States, understanding of the German position prevails.
So I don’t think it was as dramatic as the Libyan issue.
Perhaps Germany will even gain some respect in this way.
After all, this signals that she should be taken seriously as a player in the international arena and that her interests should be taken into account.
There are different views in Europe about the Palestinian initiative.
The United States, on the other hand, was clearly in favour of the veto.
Is there a difference of opinion between the United States and many European countries?
Due to American domestic policy, such differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama administration has a deep understanding of the European position.
But due to the local political situation, of course, the government cannot openly take such a position.
I believe that significant differences of opinion are not at all as significant as it always seems.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is not at all enthusiastic about Netanyahu’s policies.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the United States on the one hand and the position of a major partner in the EU on the other?
I think that’s what makes the situation so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a unified, non-contradictory European policy, but this is not the case now.
Therefore, they cannot take a broader approach and are instead forced to act on the basis of their own vision of the situation.
This is what they do with the euro.
I think that in the future Germany will take the lead in developing a common European position.
It is clear that this is not easy for Germany, at least because of its ties with Israel.
This topic has always been sensitive.
But I think it is clear to the Germans that they should play a more independent role.
If Germany sees itself as an important international player, will it not really take the lead?
Or is Germany still having a hard time leading the way?
Germany has not yet become accustomed to this, it is still always unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult to play a significant role.
Consider, for example, the euro crisis - every time Germany takes on an important role, a variety of anti-German feelings are manifested.
The Germans can’t just deal with it.
Actually, this is an old problem: you don’t want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more difficult situation than the United States.
It must take into account a wide variety of neighbors and opinions, and this is not easy.
So, the influence of the United States in European politics is constantly weakening, but at the moment the EU is not filling this vacuum, who then remains?
The Germans have a bigger role to play.
Even if you do not like it, unpleasant or increases dislike for you - this is life!
Stephen Szabo is the deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institution where academics and political scientists from Europe and North America jointly explore the problems of the transatlantic community.
In addition, Szabo is a member of the German Marshall Fund, in which he specializes in German politics, U.S. foreign policy, and transatlantic ties.
“Trademark Protection” in China: When Puma and Armani Suddenly Become Chinese
Armani is a world-renowned brand, and the Polo Ralph Lauren is.
What is the Armani Polo?
It is a completely official registered name in China, which has nothing to do with the companies from which it is formed.
However, it will be protected until the owners of the original names file a lawsuit.
It is unclear whether they will be able to uphold their rights.
“Foreigners are finding it increasingly difficult to protect their trademarks in China,” said Thomas Pattloch, a Taylor Wessing lawyer specializing in trademark infringement in the Far East.
On my desk every week there is a new case of this kind.
It is enough for imitators to add just a couple of letters to get the right to register their trademarks.
So from Gucci is Lu-Gucci, instead of Prada you can register Prada-Kny.
