Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the most important sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and tripper (gonorrhea).
Frequent viral STIs are HIV, human papillomavirus, genital herpes and hepatitis.
Pulmonary pediculosis and scabies are parasitic STIs.
What are the main affected groups?
Syphilis and gonorrhea occur mainly in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute estimates that at least four out of every five cases of syphilis reported in Germany result from sexual contact between men.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia infections, trichomoniasis, candidiasis (fungus), gonorrhea, and human papillomavirus are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The prevalence of HIV among heterosexual adults is relatively low, but about 20 per cent of new HIV infections occur in this group.
Among young people, chlamydia infections occur significantly more often than among other population groups.
According to European data, three quarters of all infections affect young people aged 15 to 25 years.
We also often have human papillomavirus among young people.
How does the number of infections change?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to mandatory registration.
The incidence of syphilis, according to the Robert Koch Institute, more than doubled from 1,697 cases in 2001 to 3,698 cases in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has been decreasing since 2007.
In 2011, there were about 2,700 cases.
That’s about a tenth less than the previous year.
What symptoms indicate a sexually transmitted disease?
In infectious diseases, there may be ulcers in the genital area, complaints when urinating, discharge, pain in the lower abdomen, as well as bubbles or seals.
However, they are often not accompanied by pain and other symptoms and go unnoticed.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but do not provide 100% protection.
After all, part of the pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be spread by contact infection and with close physical contact.
Therefore, experts recommend regular examination, especially with frequent change of sexual partners.
Early diagnosis can cure most STIs and avoid long-term consequences.
