“Instead of strengthening the civil state, the president de facto abolished it,” Saeda said.
Without civil society organizations, democracy cannot function.
Saeda feels that everyone has left him, even the international community, which looks at the ideological struggle of the Nile directions with a mixture of curiosity and tension.
There could be a payoff for that.
A protester in Tahrir Square warns: “You are creating a monster you can’t control.”
Norwegian rakfisk: the worst smelling fish in the world?
Norway’s population of five million has one of the highest living standards not only in Europe, but worldwide.
Perhaps the secret of the success of this country is somehow connected with the local addiction to one extremely mean fish dish?
Take a few overripe pieces of cheese.
Put them in a pile of dirty and sweaty sportswear.
Leave them there for a week.
You will get the smell of Rakfisk, one of the most famous Norwegian delicacies.
I am in a small town called Fagernes, three hours from Oslo.
Around the snow-covered picturesque views. It is very beautiful, but in the air spilled inexhaustible characteristic smell.
Rakfisk is a trout sprinkled with salt and roamed in the water for up to a year, depending on what kind of sweet tooth you need to achieve.
As twilight thickens and cools, crowds of Norwegians gather for a festival in Fagernes, dedicated to this very, let’s say, exciting dish.
"It is eaten raw and sipped with a glass of aquavit, a local caraway vodka," explains Howard Halvarsen, a local firefighter by profession and part-time "Rakfisk general" who leads the festival.
All around us, people eat cut into small cubes of fish and drink it with considerable portions of alcohol.
“Somebody likes Aquavit better than Rakfisk,” says Howard.
This drink can break the odor.
I'm trying a few pieces.
If you manage to carry a piece under your nose, then everything is not so bad - it is not much different from the portion of sushi that you took with you on the bus for a long time.
Rakfisk is a Norwegian product from a completely different time, the time of poverty, when, even before the advent of refrigerators, fish was soaked in hermetically sealed barrels with salt water in the autumn.
Then in the deep winter, when the fish was already well and thoroughly fermented, it was extracted and, muffling the perception with alcohol, was eaten.
Thousands of Norwegians have been forced to leave their country in search of work and emigrate, mainly to the United States.
Now the population is growing rapidly - more than 13% are immigrants, who are attracted here by jobs, high wages and a developed social security system.
Residents of Sweden (a long-time rival, and not so long ago and much more prosperous neighbor) come massively here to work.
Rakfisk is perceived as an important symbol, an indispensable, albeit somewhat stinking element of Norway’s past.
It is one of the most expensive local dishes.
On the other hand, everything is expensive here – a small glass of beer or a sandwich will cost you <0xC2><0xA3>9 ($14).
Norway rarely appears in the world news, and most residents of the country seem to be satisfied with this.
People here are still reluctant to mention the name of Anders Breivik, a racist and right-wing extremist who shot and killed 77 men, women and children last year.
Without mentioning his name, the attack is called “the July 22 incident”.
It is very difficult for Norwegians to believe that in their peace-loving country one of their fellow citizens was capable of such atrocities and murders.
Norway’s current prosperity is based on the growth (since the early seventies) of one of the largest oil and gas industries in the world.
“However, oil is not the only reason for our prosperity,” says Anna, our waitress, who serves trays with aged Rakfisk, a woman with long blond hair and strikingly blue eyes, embodying Nordic well-being.
We are a people, as you call it, intelligent.
Like most Norwegians, she speaks English very well.
We don't like to show off, we don't brag.
Norway is very careful with its oil - most of the revenues of the oil and gas industry is invested in a special fund created for the benefit of future generations.
In the years leading up to the global financial crisis, when everyone was wasting money they didn’t have, Norway was sparingly calculating all the costs.
“As long as you can ski in the winter and go hiking in the summer, that’s enough for happiness,” says Anna.
"And there is Rakfisk," she adds with a carefree laugh.
I'm standing in the snow waiting in line for some food - enough rakfiska with me.
Here's a hamburger with moose meat - it's certainly exotic, delicious juicy meat.
But in the evening we are waiting for even more of the same fish with an unforgettable smell.
In my hotel there is a special dinner dedicated to rakfisk, during which visitors vote to determine the best or perhaps the most fragrant fish.
There is a live TV show showing the presenter in a butterfly tie, surrounded by plates with rakfisk.
It's like the Eurovision Song Contest.
"So, Thor-Jürgen, what rating did you get for the best fish out there in the mountains?"
"Yes, Howard, here's our estimate."
Everyone laughs and applauds.
Someone falls out of a chair, possibly overwhelmed by an aquavit.
Or maybe just by smelling the fish.
Mexican President Enrique Peña Nieto has a tough start to his career.
As Mexican President-elect Enrique Peña Nieto prepares to take office, BBC correspondent Will Grant invites us to take a look at the challenges he will face and the mixed expectations of his country’s population.
Traffic in Mexico City is in a particularly deplorable state.
This city is overloaded with traffic and at its best, and since Monday, steel barriers have been erected, cutting off several key highways to the capital and causing chaos on the roads.
However, this was not done to prevent people from getting to work from the suburbs, but to prevent protesters from getting to the parliament building.
On Sunday, the new head of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, will wear a presidential bandage and take the reins of the country.
He faces a difficult task.
Mexico has achieved good economic performance under the administration of Felipe Calderon, which is now relinquishing its power, but the country is plunged into a war against drugs, which has already claimed about 60,000 lives in six years.
“My government declares to the people of Mexico its readiness to fight violence,” Mr. Peña Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama earlier this week in the White House’s Oval Office.
I am going to propose a new security strategy that will allow us to achieve this goal.
Before such statements, next to the US President, Mr. Peña Nieto’s political career developed as governor of his home state of Mexico.
In his homeland, in the densely populated and vast state surrounding the country’s capital, opinions about the new leader were divided.
Straight-linear man
In the idyllic town of Valle de Bravo, for example, it is remembered with warmth.
Residents are credited with revitalizing tourism, developing the resort sector and creating infrastructure.
The city can be reached by one of the new highways built by Mr. Peña Nieto, which are strikingly different from the roads with holes and pits that were previously at this place.
His name tags hang on the modern building of the sports center and on the impressive interactive museum dedicated to climate change.
“We have hopes for real and serious change,” says his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernández, a state congressman from the Peña Nieto-led Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI).
We look forward to the real and decisive changes that our country so urgently needs, especially in the area of security and economic development.
After 81 years in power, the PRI party was ousted in 2000 by Vicente Fox.
Congressman Olvera admits that after his 12-year absence from the Los Pinos presidential palace, the party has high hopes for Enrique Peña Nieto.
In addition, he denies the accusations of insubordination made by the opposition to the new president.
He is very straightforward and very dedicated to the realization of his vision of the future of the country.
He is an excellent statesman, and above all, a man who knows how to listen.
But in another part of the state, many people have a different view of the former governor.
The municipality of Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Nesa, is the most striking contrast to the cobbled streets of Valle de Bravo.
Hidden under highway overpasses, it is in many ways a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the municipality are also severe in nature of this metropolis.
Troops had been mobilized earlier this year to tame drug-trafficking gangs in those areas; violence against women was particularly acute.
Several dozen bodies of murdered women have been found in the emptiness near an extensive landfill in the last two years alone.
More than a thousand women were killed in Mexico State during the governorship of Mr. Peña Nieto, a figure that far exceeds that of the infamous city of Ciudad Juárez, whose name has become commonplace when it comes to the murder of innocent women.
According to Mr. Peña Nieto ' s opponents, at best, he had failed to address the problem of women ' s murder during his tenure as governor.
At worst, his administration is accused of completely ignoring the problem.
A resident of a concrete house similar to most of the houses in this decayed area, Irineja Buendía struggles to hold back her tears by showing me photos of her late daughter Mariana Luna.
According to the official version, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
However, her family believes that she was killed by her roommate.
“When I got to her house, it looked like her body had been washed before,” Buendía recalls.
There were signs that she had been beaten, and the body was already rigid.
Mariana’s mother retells the story, and the portrait of the daughter looks at us from the wall, where it hangs next to the crucifix, on which only one word is inscribed: justice.
This, they said, was denied to the family.
“State officials treated me like an old gossip girl, a disgruntled disturber.
They just want people to believe everything they say and keep quiet.
But this is wrong, this is not possible, especially when there are so many violations and deficiencies around," she says.
Wearing the presidential bandage on Saturday, President Peña Nieto will take on a difficult responsibility with her.
Over the past six years, tens of thousands of families in Mexico have been affected by violence-related crimes, and the new president has promised to make addressing the problem a priority during his reign.
“I hope he will be exactly the same president as he was a governor,” says Olvera, a congressman from Valle de Bravo from the PRI party.
However, this is what the families of the victims in Ciudad Nesa are most afraid of.
Bradley Manning has not complained of ill-treatment, the prosecution says.
Prosecutors are trying to disprove Bradley Manning's allegations of poor detention conditions.
During the hearing, increased attention was paid to Manning ' s stay in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense demands that the case be closed on the grounds that Manning's detention conditions were cruel.
A US soldier is accused of stealing thousands of classified documents.
On Friday, the prosecution tried to prove that Private Bradley Manning, charged with the largest leak of classified material in U.S. history, did not take advantage of multiple opportunities to file a complaint of ill-treatment, which he said he had endured while in a military prison.
During a cross-examination at a pre-trial hearing in Fort Meade, Maryland, the military prosecutor, Major Ashden Fein, stated that the records of Manning’s weekly visits by prison officials during the nine months of his detention in Quantico, Virginia, contained no complaints of ill-treatment.
The cross-examination of Manning’s motion to dismiss the case on the grounds that the conditions of his detention were cruel and in themselves sufficient punishment was conducted the day after Manning stated that while in custody, he intended to commit suicide.
A military intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 is accused of stealing several thousand classified documents while serving in Iraq.
These materials were subsequently published online on the WikiLeaks website.
WikiLeaks did not confirm that Manning was the source of the information.
At Friday’s hearing, Prosecutor Fein and Manning reviewed reports that were filled out after Manning’s visits by administration officials during his stay at Quantico Prison, where he was held under strict detention conditions from July 2010 to April 2011.
During the visits, prison officials asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Prosecutor Fein asked about the reports on Friday, Manning admitted that he rated the prison administration’s treatment of himself as “excellent” and the general conditions of the detention as “very professionally organized.”
The reports in question do not contain complaints of ill-treatment, despite Manning being directly questioned about his conditions, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed oral concerns about these issues and that the administrations visiting him had discussed these issues with him and stated that they would be addressed, but had not recorded this in writing.
“They were recording ‘there are no problems’ (after discussing my complaints), but that doesn’t mean I didn’t bring up the topic in the conversation,” Manning said.
A military judge, Colonel Denise Lindh, also asked Manning why he had not complained about his ill-treatment in January 2011 during a meeting of a commission examining suicidal intentions he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning replied that during the meeting he wanted to get rid of the “injury prevention” regime and to ease the conditions of imprisonment.
Representatives of the military leadership explained that a limited regime of detention - a level lower than the surveillance regime to prevent suicide - was introduced to protect the prisoner, as well as for the safety of others.
“I wanted to let the administration know that I’m okay so they can cancel the injury prevention regime... so that my standard of living improves, from my point of view,” Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to a prison at a naval base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He reported that he had thoughts of suicide in Kuwait, and that he had once lost consciousness due to the intense heat.
He explained that it is psychologically very difficult when you are not allowed to know how your fate is decided and what is happening in the outside world.
“My world has shrunk to Camp Arifjan base, to the size of my prison,” Manning said.
“I thought I was going to die in that cage.”
While in Quantico, Manning said, he spent most of his time in a small cell – at least 21 hours, and often more than 23 hours a day – alone.
Manning says he was only allowed to leave a mattress, a blanket, slippers, several items of clothing and glasses.
He says that he tried to move, as sleeping or even just lying down during the daytime prohibited the rules.
According to Manning, during his sleep, he was constantly hit in the eyes by light penetrating from the outside of the camera.
If the guards did not see his face when he turned over in bed at night, he said he was woken up and forced to turn over on his back.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal objection to Manning's ill-treatment in January 2011.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
Also on Friday, the judge asked Manning about a statement he made during his testimony on Thursday that after one night he was forced to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other inmates for a morning check.
Manning said he was unable to cover himself with a blanket during the inspection.
Answering the judge’s questions on Friday, Manning said he understood from the guard’s order that he should throw a blanket he could cover himself with, but admitted that no one had explicitly ordered him to throw it.
Manning said Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of his attempt to show the officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning said he told the officer that he could have used a rubber band or slippers to injure himself, but did not.
That night, according to Manning, his underwear, slippers and glasses were taken from the cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account what he had to endure during his detention and significantly shorten the length of his detention if Manning is found guilty by a military court, which is due to begin hearing his case early next year.
The defense said it plans to offer Manning a plea for less serious crimes and challenge other allegations as excessive.
The resumption of hearings is scheduled for this weekend, and the prosecution is expected to insist that conditions of detention have been justified.
The Pentagon claims that Manning was held in Quantico under the rules governing the detention of those arrested under the strictest possible regime.
The charges brought against Manning include aiding the enemy, illegally facilitating the release of data on the Internet, the transfer of information related to national defense, and the theft of state property or documents.
If he is convicted on all counts of indictment, he may face life imprisonment.
My crisis of national self-determination is the story of an American of Mexican origin.
According to the author, many Mexicans were forced to leave Mexico because of the lack of opportunities to realize themselves.
Mexicans tend to blame those who have left because they remind the people of the country of difficult times.
Ruben Navarette believes that Mexicans of American descent are torn between the two cultures.
During a recent trip to Mexico City, I walked down the arrivals corridor, approached the border control zone and froze on the spot.
The signs indicated two lines: one for Mexicanos (Mexicans), the other for Extranjeros (foreigners).
I stood in front of them for a few seconds, not knowing where to go.
I grew up in central California and have been called Mexican all my life.
It’s just a conventional name, just like my friends in Boston call themselves Irish and my friends in New York call themselves Italian.
Later, I focused on the complex construction of the "American of Mexican origin".
But here I was in Mexico.
Here, in my grandfather’s homeland, there was no need for conventional names or elaborate designs.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish well enough to ask questions or answer them.
But my vocabulary is poorer than that of native speakers, and I can’t get rid of the American accent.
So I got my American passport and made the queue for the Extranjeros.
I recalled that story a few days ago, when the newly elected President of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, visited the White House and met with President Obama.
On the agenda were the usual issues for the meetings of the presidents of these countries: immigration, drugs and trade.
President Peña Nieto happily spoke of a boom in the Mexican economy that would allow Mexicans to stay in Mexico instead of moving to the United States.
He wants to conclude a partnership agreement with the United States and Canada and create a kind of North American trade bloc like the European Union.
In addition, President Peña Nieto promised to continue the war against drug cartels in Mexico, but no specific proposals were made.
For Mexico, relations with the United States are a difficult and old-fashioned issue.
Most Americans never thought that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and, under the gun, forced its leaders to give up half of their territory.
But Mexicans think in centuries, not minutes, and see reminders of those events in everything.
Therefore, it is only necessary for any U.S. statesman to say even a word of criticism to Mexico, the press and the elite of Mexican society immediately hear complaints that Americans infringe on the sovereignty of neighbors.
And the descendants of Montezuma are filled with belligerence.
The most difficult is Mexico’s relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican-Americans living in the United States.
Do you want to talk about insults?
Enough of them.
In Mexico, there are winners and losers, people who find opportunities in this country, and those for whom such opportunities do not exist.
In Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver, or San Antonio, so many people of Mexican descent for one reason only: at some point in their family history, anyone - father or grandfather - had no opportunity to realize themselves in Mexico and was forced to go north.
Most often it was Mexicans of a certain type - brown, undereducated, from poor peasant families.
We are their descendants, and we remember that.
In Mexico, they see it differently.
Today, our lives are the embodiment of the American dream, we went to good schools and got good jobs, but we must not forget that even this dream is American, not Mexican.
Our national self-determination is confusing and unclear, but we know which country to consider as our own.
United States of America.
In addition, we know that most of the Mexican elite and the ruling class do not like us.
We respond to them the same way.
They see us as a reminder of humiliating defeats and treat us as second-class people, as untrue Mexicans.
We don’t speak Spanish well enough, and our ties with Mexico aren’t strong enough.
Our very existence for them is due to failures.
If our ancestors had succeeded in Mexico, they would not have left.
We would not be behind the silk curtain now, finding a full life in the United States, but losing spiritual ties.
My wife was born in Guadalajara and legally moved to the United States as a child, and it reminds me that there are certain frictions between real Mexicans and Americans of Mexican origin - Mexicans understand their national identity more clearly, and Americans of Mexican origin are offended by this.
She is a U.S. citizen and believes she belongs to both countries.
At the same time, many of my acquaintances of Mexican origin do not feel belonging to any of them.
We listen to the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but we also love Bruce Springsteen.
When you get the best of two worlds, you inevitably lose your roots.
In Mexico, we are Americans.
In the United States, we are called Mexicans.
Now, as I found out during my trip, as if our relationship is already insufficiently complicated, some Mexican leaders and intellectuals want to restore relations with the diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to serve as Mexico’s ambassadors and represent its interests in the United States.
We could tell our American friends about what a beautiful country it is and how great it is to visit it, and we could convince political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yeah, sure.
It's not gonna work.
Too many insults in the past.
And given the gap between rich and poor, the rampant corruption and drug trafficking, many of us do not consider this country so beautiful.
I'm sorry, but you deal with it, amigos.
And that's fair.
If some Mexicans still cannot forgive the United States for what they did to Mexico a century and a half ago, they will have to accept the fact that some Americans of Mexican descent are still resentful of how their relatives were treated in Mexico more recently.
Oh, yeah.
Maybe we have more in common than I thought.
The old battles in the new Middle East
A ceasefire agreement between Israel and Hamas could be a fragile foundation for further peace.
Is a lasting peace between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East possible?
Another round of bloodshed leads to a conclusion about the futility of such hopes.
There is a familiar, senseless debate about who started it; many buildings have been turned into ruins; over 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed; and for the first time since the conflict, rockets fired from the Gaza Strip have fallen in the vicinity of the Israeli capital Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem.
However, despite the fact that Israelis and Palestinians are hopelessly stuck in their eternal conflict, changes have come to the Middle East.
This can be treated differently, but the events of the “Arab Spring” have circled in a rebellious storm many established realities, and the Palestinians with the Israelis have not managed to stay away from the vortex that shook the region.
Perhaps, as a result, their struggle will become even more bloody than before.
However, there are reasons to hope for a way out of this deadly impasse.
A War Without Winners
At first glance, the situation does not give cause for optimism.
Even if the ceasefire, which was signed on November 21, will be implemented, the clashes this week only strengthened the positions of security forces on both sides.
The leaders of the Islamist Hamas movement, which came to power in the Gaza Strip in 2007, will say that they forced Israel to retreat despite the losses they suffered.
Despite the fact that some of the group’s leaders were killed and 1.7 million residents trapped in one of the most densely populated and troubled corners of our planet, Israel failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is growing in popularity in the West Bank, another Palestinian territory now controlled by a more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may well come to the conclusion that time is working for them.
As the influence of Islamist movements in the Arab world grows, Hamas has new influential and wealthy friends.
The resurgent regional leader, Turkey, once Israel’s closest ally among Muslim nations, has come out with support for Hamas; Qatar, one of the wealthiest and most dynamic Gulf states, has followed suit.
Triumphing Hamas supporters are claiming to have created an Islamist crescent around Israel – from Lebanon in the north, ruled by Hezbollah’s paramilitary group, to Syria, where increasingly pro-Islamist rebels are about to overthrow Bashar al-Assad, and then to Jordan, where the king’s power is threatened by Hamas allies.
The most significant shift in the balance of power in the region occurred on the southern borders of Israel, in the most populous and important Arab country, Egypt, where the influence of the Muslim Brotherhood was strengthened under President Mohammed Mursi.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was overthrown in 2011, was a secular dictator who did not pay much attention to supporting Hamas.
The Muslim Brotherhood, on the other hand, is an organization much like Hamas, and its leaders are more prone to populism.
In future diplomatic settings, Hamas may become a significant player whose voice will not be silenced even by Israel and America.
At the same time, supporters of the “hard” line in Israel will come to the opposite conclusions.
In a military sense, Hamas was defeated.
Israel’s Iron Dome anti-missile system has justified the cost of its creation and successfully destroyed many of Hamas’s missiles.
Citizens of Israel can sleep peacefully, at least for a while.
As far as diplomacy is concerned, the US has remained true to its unchanged position; many European countries have also blamed Hamas for the start of the latest round of violence.
Another important factor is the economic prosperity of Israel, especially under the government of Benjamin Netanyahu, who largely ignored the peace process.
Despite the fact that about 30 Israelis have been killed by rockets fired from the Gaza Strip since 2004, Israel has managed to minimize the problem of suicide bombers, in part due to the wall that enters the West Bank - a large part of the unrecognized Palestinian state - and protects such actions from international settlements, which continue to expand.
The position of Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party, in preparation for the January 22 elections, has teamed up with even more aggressive conservatives under the leadership of Avigdor Lieberman, is very convenient.
What’s the point of giving the Palestinians a state of their own?
If all power in the West Bank is given to them, will they not launch rockets into Israel from there, as their fellow Israelis do in the Gaza Strip?
It is better to keep them behind the wall and rigidly suppress any attempts to raise their heads.
The hardliners may be victorious; however, their calculations may be refuted by the Arab Spring.
While the Islamists who come to power in Egypt and elsewhere do not have the warmest feelings for Israel, their priority will be domestic problems.
Israel’s defense budget is larger than all of its Arab neighbors combined.
Unleashing a war with a regional superpower is unlikely to help Arab governments strengthen their own economies.
The pragmatism of Egyptian President Mursi, who has worked with Barack Obama on the ceasefire, is a good sign and may mark the beginning of change.
Israel must, no less, take into account the long-term consequences of its policies.
As democratic changes in the Arab countries occur, the deprivation of Palestinians of the right to self-determination is a time bomb that will sooner or later explode in the Israeli-occupied territories, like the bus that exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
The repression is already undermining the foundations of the democratic order in the Jewish state, and the demographic dimension – the growth of the Arab population – only exacerbates these problems.
The bloody operations that take place every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress Hamas have to be paid for by the growing discontent of the international community.
Both sides need external impulses.
The only solution that remains, which is constantly called for by sensible representatives from both sides, as well as most of the rest of the world and our newspaper: the formation of two states and Israel's concession of territories in exchange for security.
There remains a hope, not too impressive in the short term, that a ceasefire will allow other countries to influence the parties to the conflict more effectively.
Egypt, which has long since decided to cut off arms shipments to the Gaza Strip, as well as Turkey and Qatar, are more than ever in a position to persuade Hamas to recognize the borders of the Jewish state adopted since 1967, taking into account the exchange of territories and the shared use of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries should also make efforts to reconcile the Hamas and Fatah movements.
This would do more to create a Palestinian state than the upcoming UN vote, which could result in the recognition of a virtual Palestinian state.
President Obama has a role to play in bringing Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term, he never presented his own peace plan.
After returning to the White House, he continues to show reluctance to get involved in solving the problem.
This is a catastrophically short-sighted position.
The United States has a vital interest in stability in the Middle East.
This is only possible if there is a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
In Australia, the law on unified packaging for cigarettes has come into force.
Warnings about the dangers of smoking and images of affected parts of the body contrast on the sad green boxes, the same for all brands of cigarettes.
The first in the world, the Australian law on the same type of packaging of cigarettes and tobacco products came into force, replacing the logos and color design of different brands with the same box of sad-olive color with eerie pictures of affected parts of the body and images of children whose health is undermined by the smoking of their parents.
In addition to the various pictures and inscriptions warning about the dangers of smoking, the only difference between the packs introduced mandatory from this Saturday is the names of the stamps, which are printed in the same small font.
These are the harshest conditions in the world for the design of packaging of tobacco products.
The Australian federal government says the goal of the measure is to keep young people from smoking, depriving them of this bad habit of fashion status.
The study found that people who did not start smoking before the age of 26 never smoked in 99 out of 100 cases.
“It is obvious that even at a very young age, children understand the meaning that tobacco companies are trying to convey through packaging,” explains Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, referring to studies that have shown that, for example, the crown in the logo is associated in children with the idea of a princess.
Australia is one of the countries with the lowest proportion of smokers in the world, so these changes will not have much impact on the profits of transnational corporations, but other countries are already considering such measures.
Representatives of the tobacco industry strongly opposed the adoption of this law.
Tobacco companies argue that this will only increase the share of the black market, where cheap and affordable cigarettes will be sold.
“This law will have serious consequences other than those conceived by its initiators,” said Scott McIntyre, a spokesman for British American Tobacco in Australia.
Manufacturers of counterfeit products from China and Indonesia will supply much more such goods for sale on the streets of Australia.
For some, on the contrary, the new laws contribute to the growth of business.
Sandra Ha of the small family-owned Zico Import Pty Ltd claims that the demand for cigarettes and silicone cases hiding nasty pictures on the packaging has grown rapidly (almost from scratch) since two months ago companies such as British American Tobacco, British Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco tried and lost the case.
According to Sandra Ha, Zico has already sold about six thousand products to wholesalers and is expecting a new batch.
This is a good business for us.
A potential obstacle to the effectiveness of such measures is, according to experts, the popularity of social networks among the part of the population to which these measures are directed.
After Australia passed a number of laws that made television advertising of cigarettes and their support for sporting events illegal, as well as prohibiting sellers from displaying cigarettes in a prominent place, tobacco advertising has moved to the Internet.
The Australian government has banned local companies and websites from placing ads online, but it cannot restrict foreign websites from doing so.
“If you’re a tobacco trader and you’re left with just that little loophole, you’ll find the idea of promoting your product online extremely tempting,” explains Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman notes an increase in the number of trademark reviews written on behalf of supposedly ordinary users on social networks such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
The question arises - is this really the work of an ordinary citizen who loves Marlboro cigarettes so much that he spared no effort and time and made a video, or is there an advertising company behind this?
The Australian branch of British American Tobacco claims that the industry is now more busy adapting to the new rules than advertising.
The tobacco industry has even taken measures such as sponsorship of Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules: these states are making claims within the World Trade Organization, claiming that trade has been unfairly restricted, despite the fact that trade relations of all these countries with Australia are very small.
The WTO decision is expected by mid-2013.
According to Tanya Plibersek, the government has been discussing with other countries the possibility of enacting similar laws on packaging.
In 2001, Canada was the first country to make it mandatory to post photographs warning of the dangers of smoking.
Now this rule is adopted in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
The possibility of tightening the laws is being considered in the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many smokers in Australia are demonstratively disobedient to innovations.
These pictures don't bother me.
I just don't pay attention.
“You just grab a cigarette and hide a pack in your pocket,” explains Victor El Haig, who buys cigarettes with a picture of the oral tumor on the pack.
Honestly, the only thing that can make me quit is my little daughter.
James Yu, head of the King of the Pack tobacco store in downtown Sydney, claims that the same packaging has made it difficult to place goods on the shelves.
“I used to take an hour to unload a new batch, and now four hours,” he complains.
“The government should have taken and banned cigarettes altogether, then we would have said: what to do, okay, it’s over, we close the store,” he said, throwing his hands up.
Being bored in the world of electronic networks and constant connections is not so bad.
On this Thanksgiving day, I had to spend five hours at the airport because our plane had a mechanical malfunction and was replaced with another plane, which we were waiting for.
So I had plenty of time to reflect on the nature of boredom.
I'm not gonna lie to you.
Half a day at the airport waiting for the flight is really boring, and neither books, nor magazines, nor iPhones, nor even duty-free stores will help much.
Recently, however, more and more scientists and specialists in child development have spoken in favor of boredom.
They say that in certain situations for us and for our children to miss is not so bad.
This forces the brain to be distracted by interesting related topics, which may contribute to creativity.
And since in the modern world we are all constantly in front of some screen, the benefits of boredom pass us by.
Maybe we should strive for boredom?
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
And at the same time, no.
We'll get back to that.
I used to think that boredom was an invention of relatively recent times, when people had more free time.
This is not the case, says Peter Tui, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada, author of Boredom: A Lively History, Yale University Press, 2011.
“In fact, boredom has a very ancient history,” he says.
On the walls of Pompeii found Latin inscriptions about boredom, dating back to the first century.
The question remains as to how we understand boredom.
The problem, says John D. Eastwood, an associate professor at York University in Ontario, Canada, is that the understanding and vision of boredom has often changed.
After reviewing research materials on the subject and asking a 100-person target group a question, Professor Eastwood and colleagues came up with the following definition: Boredom is when people “want but can’t do what would satisfy them.”
The difference between boredom and apathy, he says, is that a bored person doesn’t do something they’d like to do.
With apathy, you don’t want to do anything.
The core of boredom, he says, is “disruption of attention and the associated deterioration of mood and the feeling that time is slow.”
The description of boredom can seem very similar to depression.
However, Professor Eastwood argues that despite the possible connection between these conditions, bored people see the causes of problems in the world and circumstances, and people experiencing depression see problems in themselves.
Sometimes we feel bored when it’s really hard to focus on something.
In his study, “Unoccupied Mind: Defining Boredom in terms of Attention,” published in the September issue of the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and colleagues cite an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a recording of a voice reading the journal.
Some participants also heard the loud sounds of a non-relevant television program turned on in the next room, others heard the same sounds at a low volume, so that they could hardly be disassembled, and the third group listened only to the recording of a voice without an outside soundtrack.
Those participants who heard the low-loud television said they were bored, more often than others - they found it difficult to concentrate, but they didn't know the reason for it and attributed it to boredom.
When we try to focus on a difficult or exciting task, interrupting attention can be boring, says Mark J. Fenske, an associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph, Ontario, and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, when we do something uninteresting, “for example, looking at the flow of products on the conveyor in search of marriage, distracting music can help to avoid boredom.”
It is believed that when people begin to swing on a chair or draw scribbles on a piece of paper, they do it out of boredom, but now we know that such actions simply help not to relax physically.
"The study showed that children who are not forbidden to swing and spin learn better and memorize more information than children who are required to sit quietly," says Professor Fenske.
At some point, we all feel bored: when the flight is delayed (as in my case), listening to a monotonous speech, watching an uninteresting movie.
However, different people show varying degrees of boredom.
In the 1980s, researchers developed a special “boring tendency scale” to measure such individual features.
Questions and statements are used to determine the rating on such a scale, for example, "Many of what I have to do is monotonous and monotonous" or "I am interested in too much, so there is no time for anything."
With the help of such questionnaires, the researchers determined that boys miss girls more often, - says Stephen Wodanovich, professor of psychology at the University of Western Florida - especially in the presence of a variety of external stimuli.
However, in general, teenagers are often bored.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of personal and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted almost 400 teenagers and their parents 7-8 times a day via a pager.
The results were as follows: 32% of teens said they were bored at school and while doing homework, and 23% said they were bored outside of school.
Only 3% of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson notes that he has no data on what such data on boredom would be now, 21 years later.
However, he knows that “teenagers are at the peak of boredom,” mainly because children and adolescents are not allowed to fully decide what to do.
Back to my original question: Is boredom useful?
Sometimes not, because in extreme manifestations, research shows, it can push people to absurd and dangerous physical activities, risky gambling or substance abuse in an attempt to get rid of boredom.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers have thought about the connection between boredom and creativity, says Professor Vodanovich, who has devoted more than two decades to the study of this problem.
“So our brains tell us to do something else; that’s boredom,” says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at New York University.
However, this same brain does not always know what exactly is best to do.
If you get bored and you focus that energy on playing the guitar or cooking experiences, you will do better for yourself.
However, if you start watching TV, you will only get better for a while, and soon it will pass.
Therefore, if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he will cease to be bored, but he will not learn to cope with boredom on his own or in any other way to manage his time and employment, - says Professor Fenske.
“Such self-regulation skills are used in a variety of situations,” he argues.
Your child is not only learning to do something on their own, he is also learning self-control in general.
I don't think boredom should be praised.
However, it is not worth considering it as something bad either.
Rather, you should learn to feel comfortable even outside the continuous flow of activities and technology.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
“We see it as something that we need to get bored more often, while boredom is an extremely unpleasant, insatiable desire to do something meaningful,” he says.
In fact, people tend to somehow disconnect from constant worries and just relax.
“In today’s world, we are accustomed to the constant overstimulation of the senses,” he says, “and when silence comes, we get lost and don’t know what to do.”
It is not yet clear how the new law on the legalization of marijuana in the state of Colorado will be applied
Anthony Orozco, a 19-year-old football team player and student at a community college in southeastern Colorado, is accused of committing a criminal offense that will soon be completely legal throughout the state: possession of a small portion of marijuana and the tube in which he smoked it.
Mr. Orosco says that one September he and his friends were in Lamar driving a car along the prairie near the Kansas border when they were stopped by police.
After a police officer discovered marijuana in his car, Mr. Orozco was subpoenaed for possession of drugs and possession of a device for drug use - minor offences for which a fine of $100 was owed - and a trial date was set.
“We are treated like criminals,” says Mr. Orozco.
But is he a criminal?
As a result of the uncertainty that continues for several weeks after the state of Colorado voted to legalize the use of small amounts of marijuana for entertainment, the decision of hundreds of small court cases depends not so much on the law, but on the place of consideration.
Charges of minor marijuana offences have already been dropped in hundreds of cases here and in Washington State, which has taken a similar measure.
Police departments have already stopped charging people aged 21 and over for storing low doses, which will be considered legal as soon as the law comes into force in a couple of weeks.
However, in the more conservative districts of Colorado, prosecutors have decided to review existing marijuana cases and continue to prosecute the possession of the drug.
At the same time, in some cities from the suburbs of Denver to the mountainous areas of the West voted to prevent the emergence of new, state-licensed stores selling marijuana in their places.
“It’s all happening so fast that I don’t know what to expect next,” said Daniel J. Oates, chief of police in the town of Aurora, east of Denver.
Representatives of the regulatory bodies in the state of Washington are also scratching their heads in confusion.
They have to form rules to determine the licensing procedure for the cultivation, processing, distribution and sale of marijuana, and all this must be done by December 1, 2013.
They say Colorado, good or bad, is ahead of most other states in regulating marijuana use, first for medical purposes and now for entertainment.
“There’s a more streamlined market in Colorado, so they’ll set a good example,” explains Brian E. Smith, a representative of the Council for the Regulation of the Production and Sales of Alcohol in Washington.
But now no one can do more, admits Mr. Smith, than put forward some proposals and hope that it will work.
“We don’t have a real precedent to follow,” he said.
The Washington state bill, dubbed I-502, will go into effect on December 6 and plunge the state into a state of uncertainty for a year when the state licensing system is not yet in place and marijuana ownership is already legal.
But there are still difficult technical aspects that need to be addressed during this period, for example, how to find a balance between the state's order to "adequate access" to licensed marijuana with a ban on its trade at a distance of 1000 feet from schools, parks, playgrounds and kindergartens.
“It will be particularly difficult to place licensed marijuana businesses within cities, particularly in Seattle and its suburbs,” said Ben Livingston, a spokesman for the newly formed Marijuana Legalization Center.
On November 21, police chief Oates of Aurora emailed his subordinates that the city’s prosecutor’s office would no longer hold people over the age of 21 responsible for possession of a small amount of marijuana, and that police would stop indicting people for those violations “from now on.”
Chief Oates said the police would monitor the city’s regulations governing medical marijuana growers and would prosecute illicit drug traffickers and distributors.
Weld County Attorney in northern Colorado, Ken Buck, is taking a more rigorous approach to the matter.
After the vote on the bill, he said prosecutors would continue to prosecute possession of marijuana, mainly to encourage users to undergo treatment.
At the moment, 119 individuals are charged with possession of two ounces or less of marijuana, although many are accused of other violations.
"It is the duty of our institution to prosecute for acts that are considered criminal at the time they are committed," Buck said in a statement.
The reaction was mixed even in places like the Mesa rural district, where voters rejected the proposal to legalize marijuana.
The police of Grand Junction, the largest city in the county, no longer hold adults accountable for possession of a small amount of the drug.
District Attorney Pete Hautzinger supported the decision, but also decided not to drop the charges in the already open cases related to marijuana possession.
“I believe that enforcing the law until it changes is our direct duty,” he said.
While 55% of Colorado voters supported the decision, incorporating marijuana use for entertainment into the state and legal system will not be easy.
And the controversial reaction of residents in different parts of the state exposed the ambiguity of the attitude of local authorities to the state experiment with marijuana.
“The district attorneys have a cultural barrier to this,” explains Sean McAllister, a Denver-based lawyer representing convicts of marijuana possession and a local representative of the National Marijuana Law Reform Organization.
“They’ve harassed people for so long that they can’t really put up with the fact that it’s no longer a crime,” he says.
Colorado and Washington, the first states to treat a small amount of marijuana in the same way as alcohol, are destined to become a country-wide experimental field to test the very idea of drug legalization.
Proponents of legalization and state officials plan to expand the territory of legalized trade, but at the same time they are wary of instructions from the federal authorities, who still plan to consider the sale and cultivation of marijuana as federal crimes.
Proponents of marijuana legalization hope that the Justice Department will yield in this matter.
Despite several high-profile arrests of drug traffickers and medical marijuana users, the federal government has in most cases approved medical marijuana trafficking in Colorado, Washington, and 16 other states.
Drug Enforcement Office agents are unlikely to break into homes to seize a small package of marijuana, but they are unlikely to turn a blind eye to state-regulated recreational marijuana stores that are allowed under the new law, says Kevin A. Sabet, a former anti-drug adviser in the Obama administration.
Some cities in Colorado did not wait for the action of the federal authorities.
Even before the presidential election, some local administrations approved a moratorium on the opening of new marijuana stores, which would not have been able to open sooner than a year later.
Last week, Montrose, a city in the western part of the state, put forward a six-month ban on the trade in marijuana, which is likely to be approved next week.
“We don’t want to be in a position where we give someone a license and then it will cause serious problems at the federal level,” said Bob Nicholson, a member of the city council.
The city voted against the amendment.
And now we have a contradiction between the results of the local vote and what the state voted for.
There are still many unresolved issues.
Petronella Wyatt: I survived Oxford for being a Conservative.
The persecution of university students for their views did not begin today.
For as long as I can remember, I’ve always dreamed of going to Oxford University.
My father and older brother studied at Oxford and described it as the best educational institution in the world, a modern analogue of the ancient symposium, laying the two foundations of civilization - freethinking and tolerance.
And yet, after two weeks of studying at the history faculty of the Worcester College of Oxford in the late eighties, I packed my suitcases and left, which resulted in the first real scandal in my life.
My father couldn't stand it and cried.
My friends were confused.
The Evening Standard claimed that I dropped out of college because I didn’t like my classmates having sex in the next room.
Writer E. Norman Wilson joked that I had left because I had to drink from the squeezed cups.
It wasn't really that much fun.
I ran away.
Yeah, I ran because I was being systematically poisoned and bullied.
Not at all because of my rather unusual name or the fact that I went to a private school.
I was poisoned for one reason only, and in this glorious cradle of enlightenment it seemed true barbarism and blind fanaticism: my father, now deceased Woodrow Wyatt, was a well-known adviser to Margaret Thatcher, and I myself was a supporter of the Conservatives.
You may ask, why remember this now?
According to the latest data, a new generation of students who adhere to center-right views are subjected to the same harassment.
This institutionalized and ever-increasing hatred of conservative students in Oxford is so strong that last week a group of such students demanded the same protection of their rights as that granted to disabled, sexual and ethnic minorities.
Conservatives from the Corpus Christi College student club in Cambridge say they are “often actively isolated, subjected to personal attacks and made to feel like unwanted guests” because of their political views.
They want to introduce an additional representative to the college’s Equal Rights Committee to ensure freedom of expression.
Their situation was only aggravated by the recently released BBC 2 documentary on student politics, Wonderland: Young, Smart and Right, in which conservatives were portrayed as eccentrics and neo-Nazis.
The film features Joe Cook, former president of the Conservative Association of Oxford University, who rides in a Rolls Royce, wears a silver suit and a cane with a silver cap.
In other universities, conservative students complain that they are being made "goats for higher tuition fees."
Luke Black, 20, vice president of the Conservative Association of the University of Nottingham, said in an interview with a Sunday newspaper that “in the university environment, the bias towards left-wing views is increasing.
People who don’t even know us think we are impudent and impunity-ridden children of rich parents.”
Samuel Roberts, 21, a college history student at Corpus Christi College who has filed a request for increased protection, calls the atmosphere “uncomfortable,” and Stephanie Cheryl, 19, the new president of the Conservative Association at Oxford University, says the student club’s attitude toward center-right viewers has deteriorated significantly.
“This poses a threat both to the atmosphere of intellectual discussion and simply to the normal life of the club members,” she said.
The first few weeks in Oxford I was not just in the minority, I was alone.
I went there in September 1986, a shy and shy 18-year-old girl.
Oxford was in a frenzy of hatred for the Conservative Party.
A year earlier, the university had voted to deprive former student Margaret Thatcher of her honorary degree due to budget cuts to higher education.
In such an atmosphere, even the Stalinists would be uncomfortable.
In the first days of the freshman week, when students get to know each other and the teachers, I felt for the first time what was ahead of me.
I did not know that the teachers not only looked over their fingers at the harassment of conservative students, but also gladly took part in it.
Political issues—miners’ strike, privatization, and the government’s disagreement to impose sanctions on the apartheid government in South Africa—were sweeping through the paneled walls of the auditorium.
At my first seminar, I had to translate the French text of the eighteenth century into English, and I was not ready for what followed.
"Miss Wyatt," said the professor, now deceased Harry Pitt, "please translate the first paragraph."
The text was difficult for me, I was stunned.
Harry Pitt was a very bile-like person with a cake-like face.
"Thatcherists don't teach French in principle, or they just don't have the brains?" he asked.
The other students giggled.
There were tears in my eyes.
“I would advise you to take a few basic French lessons in your spare time, unless you’re very busy revolving around society,” Pitt said.
I went back to my room completely unhappy.
That night in college, I was sitting alone for lunch; then someone patted me on the shoulder.
It was James, a second-year student from the faculty of English, who introduced himself as a member of the Conservative Association of the University.
“I know who you are,” he said friendly.
- Unfortunately, the situation is as follows:
Anyone who is suspected of being sympathetic to the Conservatives will be bullied.
It's not easy for me, and in your case, they know that your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it's going to be harder for you.
Most Conservative freshmen pretend to be Labour.”
Later, in the local pub, I cowardly tried to be hypocritical.
I insisted that I didn’t agree with everything Margaret Thatcher said.
The trick failed.
A first-year student of the Faculty of Philosophy, Politics and Economics, who himself studied at Eton, said: “You are the daughter of a fascist pig.
You are contagious.”
The other students picked up his words.
I was spoiled, dirty.
“How do conservatives have sex?” one of them asked.
- They're hitting each other, aren't they?"
I felt the way homosexuals must have felt before the abolition of criminal prosecution in the 1960s.
Will I ever be able to live a normal life in Oxford?
Or do I have to meet with like-minded people only under the cover of the night?
Will I be forced to become a Labour leader and hide my true beliefs?
The next three years began to seem like hell, full of persecution and loneliness.
The only professor in my college who did not hide his conservative views was Norman Stone, a professor of modern history.
He was hated not only for belonging to the Conservatives, but also for being Thatcher’s foreign policy adviser and one of its speechwriters.
He barely showed up for college.
He despised him for his provinciality, pettiness, and adherence to a Marxist-determinist view of history.
In 1997, he accepted a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
"You won't be happy here," he told me.
I began to travel to Oxford from my parents’ home in London, trying to find refuge among relatives and unbiased friends of the capital.
I told my father I hated Oxford and explained why.
He didn't believe me.
During his studies in the 1940s, all political views were accepted there.
“But it’s the best university in the world,” he said.
- They can't do that, except in a city of dormant spires...
Even my communist friends have always behaved flawlessly.”
His wet eyes blurred.
“Don’t make hasty decisions.
I'm sure it's just a joke.
You'll break my heart if you quit college."
I was exhausted by my constant travels to London and my emotional defenses were weakening.
My friend, also a conservative, could not stand the pressure and renounced his beliefs.
The following week, during a seminar, when another history teacher called me the “enemy of the people” quite seriously, I decided to do the same.
In my heart, burning with shame, I confessed that “my parents brainwashed me” and called them “old fools.”
The respite was short-lived.
The last nail in the coffin cover of my career in Oxford was destined to nail my father.
At the time, he wrote two columns a week for publications belonging to Rupert Murdoch.
My door was locked.
I did not go out, and five minutes later my pursuers surrendered.
When they left, I packed my suitcase and took the first train to London.
I never came back.
You can call me a weeping and a rag.
But at the age of eighteen, no one should become the object of such anger and intimidation in an educational institution.
All the more sad that it was Oxford, which not only released fourteen Tory prime ministers, but still hides behind the undeserved reputation of a university that values equality and freedom of thought.
"Valentino prefers elegance to glory"
About the exhibition "Valentino: master of sewing", which opened this week in London, ABC talks with Nati Abascal, Fiona Thyssen-Bornemitz and other famous clients of the Italian designer
Somerset House, the former residence of Queen Elizabeth I of England, is the only place in the British capital worthy of hosting an exhibition about Valentino Garavani.
The designer acknowledged this during the opening of “Valentino: Master of Sewing”, a triumphant retrospective exhibition that brings together more than 130 high fashion dresses created by his “home” over the past 50 years.
"I love this palace," he says with his unique Italian accent.
This exhibition is the final part of the story, the only character of which is "il señore" Garavani, but it could not have been written without his eminent clients.
Valentino has always felt fascinated by the rare and distant world of the nobility.
The first hall of this exhibition, open until March 3, abounds with personal letters and photographs signed by the most eminent aristocrats, from Princess Salima Aga Khan to Lord Snowdon, including Marie-Chantal, Princess of Greece, and Margaret, Princess of Great Britain.
Valentino shows these personal memories as trophies of his social rise: from a modest tailor from the city of Voghera in northern Italy to the idol of the international "elite".
Being in love with the royal court is not a bad thing.
“At least they’re not extinguishing their cigarettes on your gorgeous carpet like some great pop stars do,” says Baroness Fiona Thyssen-Bornemitz.
In the 60s and 70s, we both lived in the Alps and were good friends.
Valentino is an unparalleled host and welcomes guests with generosity and elegance.
“We all loved coming to his chalet in Gstaad,” explains Heini’s ex-wife Thyssen, a close friend of forgotten beauties like Marella Agnelli or Eugenia Niarchos.
Valentino has always preferred elegance to fame.
And yet, he is a star.
Valeria Mazza, representing Valentino
Argentine model Valeria Mazza remembers the charismatic fashion designer.
One day we went to his house for dinner, it was after a fashion show in Piazza di Spagna in Rome, many years ago.
Among the twenty guests were Sharon Stone and John Kennedy Jr.
Valentino's style manifested itself in everything - in every detail of his apartment, in her decor, in food, in music.
“Each of Valentino’s guests made him feel important and loved,” recalls the “top model” whose work with the fashion designer began in 1995 during the Paris Fashion Week.
“He never goes out of style because his sketches are real works of art,” she concludes.
Pedigree Parade
The life of Garawani is not a story of obsessions, but of falling in love with complete reciprocity.
He loves people with good upbringing and high titles, and they love him.
One of the galleries of the Somerset House of somersaults was transformed into a glamourous podium of sixty meters in length, which offers a change of roles: the visitor takes the place of the models and must parade on the podium, contemplating the "spectators" of the dreams that shine in the masterpieces of Valentino, such as the dress that Ardaud Kennedy chose for his wedding.
In this audience, such names as Sibylle of Luxembourg, Gloria von Thurn und Taxis, Mette-Marit from Norway, Rosario from Bulgaria or Sophia Habsburg shine from the models.
Nati Abascal and fashion designer, 2006
Many of these clients say that Valentino’s first love is “impossible to forget.”
I remember him perfectly.
These were trousers, a shirt, a "vest" and a jacket from the autumn-winter 1971-1972 collection.
“It was a gift he gave me,” says Nati Abascal, one of the designer’s muses.
"I prefer him to the rest for his femininity, for his great love for women, because he emphasizes our beauty," the former Duchess of Feria added.
I really like the colors he uses: they have a lot of light and they “fit” into his face.
The proportions are ideal.
Princess and fashion legislator Patricia della Giovampaola d'Arenberg also can not forget the first time she dressed in Valentino.
When I was a teenager living in Italy, I dreamed that I would have the age and reason to wear one of his evening toilets.
That time finally came in the late 1990s.
I bought my first dress from Valentino to wear it for a holiday in the castle of my cousin, Prince Edward de Ligne.
It was a red dress, with a skirt with curls, "corsage" in the fold and a neckline without straps.
“It was a dream that came true,” says Rodrigo d’Arenberg’s widow.
“Valentino is indifferent to fashion, his passion is timeless,” explains this Italian aristocrat, who lives between Paris, New York and Buenos Aires.
Princess d'Arenberg keeps her festive dresses from the fashion designer with "extreme caution ... because a dress is not just a dress, it is also a collection of memories accompanying it."
The "King" of Fashion
The grand finale of the exhibition at Somerset House is Marie-Chantal Miller's wedding dress for her wedding to Pavlos from Greece in 1995.
It took four months of work and 25 "girls" (as the designer calls his seams) to make this outfit of ivory silk with an inlay of pearls, twelve kinds of different laces and a four-and-a-half-meter plume.
According to journalist Suzy Menkes, the greatest authority of the specialized press, the dress represents a milestone of high fashion of the end of the 20th century, "the return of clients from the higher world."
Overwhelmed by the elite’s “lifestyle” for many years, Valentino himself is now the elite’s best representative.
Knight of the Grand Cross (an insignia of the highest rank in Italy), Knight of Labor, Commander of the Order of Arts and Letters, awarded the Order of the Legion of Honor, Garavani collected as many honors as any of the spouses of his clients.
"My attention has always been drawn to his sophistication, his calmness, his neat and impeccable appearance," recalls d'Arenberg.
The last time I saw him was a month ago at a gala dinner at the Orsay Museum.
He sat at the table with the Countess Jacqueline de Ribe, my great friend.
"He was impeccable, time does not exist for him."
If that's what the princess says...
The most difficult profession in the world: miners from Kawah-Ijena
For four euros, Indonesian miners risk their lives and health by dragging 70 kilograms of sulfur to the top of the volcano along steep rocky paths
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
Among them is Anto Vijaya, one of 400 miners who make a living mining sulfur in the Kawah-Ijen volcano, located in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Every day, Anto descends to the very bottom of the crater, where sulfur gas rising from the depths of the Earth freezes in contact with air.
He cuts off huge chunks of sulfur, the total weight of which can reach 70 kg, he puts them in two bamboo baskets, rolls the baskets on his shoulders and carries them up the cliffed rocky road.
To the top of the volcano, which is 2,386 meters high, only 250 meters, however, exhausted loaders need more than 40 minutes to climb the turtle step, with difficulty keeping balance and carefully tapping the road, so as not to stumble and fall from the cliff.
They know that one wrong step can cost them their lives, as happened to one tourist from France who fell from the cliffs of Kawah-Ijena a few years ago.
Kawah-Ijena miners earn 5 cents for every kilogram of sulfur they extract
Once upstairs, they pave their way between tourists who photograph them as if they were circus monkeys and, weary of carrying heavy baskets, walk three kilometers to the scales, which the mining company has placed a little higher, at an altitude of 1,850 meters.
We are talking about PT Kandi Ngrimbi, an enterprise that has been operating this volcano since 1960 and, better to say, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) for every kilogram of sulfur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) to petrochemicals, because this mineral is common in everyday life and is used for the manufacture of matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even for bleaching sugar.
"Since the norm is carrying 70 kilograms, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each walk," explains Anto, who usually performs three daily carry-overs.
He spends three hours on each of them and at the end feels broken, but they allow him to accumulate 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) by the end of the day.
Although it seems miserable for such an inhuman effort, it is three times what he would earn in the field.
"The daily fee for miners is very high by local standards, where the coffee collection is paid 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) per day and the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros)," explains the loader, who used to work as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There his salary was 75,000 rupees (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>6.2) a day and the plot was not so heavy, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a town near the volcano, for a good reason that in Indonesia is as crushing as sulfur: "I married a girl from Bali, where only Hindus took Yavu, and brought her home."
Anto has asthma, he breathes with difficulty, constantly coughs, and his eyes are tearful due to toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto spent three years risking himself in Kawah-Ijen, whose sulfur has already begun to affect him despite the presence of a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, he breathes with difficulty, he coughs constantly, and his eyes are tearing because of the toxic gases that the volcano emits.
This is the price he has to pay to achieve his dream.
“I’m going to work two more years because I want to open a store or learn Spanish or French,” he promised in more than acceptable English.
Punished with life, this pleasant and intelligent young man could be a tour guide, waiter, or hotel porter, but instead he does the job of a mule.
Sharing a dirty wooden hut with other porters, he gets up every day at 2:00 a.m. because the sulfur does not stop flowing out at night when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the dark.
Challenged by the shadows, Anto descends into the crater, illuminating his path with a small lantern connected to his helmet, which he himself bought with his own money.
About 400 porters drag baskets with gray on their shoulders from the bottom of the volcano
Despite the high profits, the mining company has not mechanized sulfur mining to save costs and does not provide any equipment to porters who work on their own account and with such deprivations.
In fact, they don’t even get part of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) photo fee, which, along with the 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) entry ticket, the reserve’s guards charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its mule people.
“It’s a job for cattle, not for people,” said Badrusin, a 42-year-old rooted bearer who has spent three decades in Kawah-Ijena since leaving college.
Capable of lifting up to 110 kilograms, he assures that he will tolerate the job “as much as he can” because he needs money to educate his three children aged 18 to 10.
I’m not going to retire, I’m going to die here, because volcano is my whole life.
Although the sulfur burns the throat and burns the eyes when the wind suddenly changes and catches the miners in dense pillars of smoke coming out of the volcano, they are so hardy that no one complains of their serious illnesses... more serious, apparently, than their usual breathing problems, arthrosis, knee pains and sores on the shoulders, which are more severe than the ulcers on the shoulders.
Balancing the basket on his back, Unainik can now only lift 50 kilograms in his 53 years.
Every day, he and his comrades take 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks transport to a warehouse in Tamansari, covering a distance of 18 kilometers along a narrow path among the thickets.
“I’m not going to retire, I’m going to die here, because the volcano is my whole life,” Unaynik said, opening his mouth wide and missing a few teeth.
Of his five children, the eldest, 30 years old, also works as a sulfur carrier.
Time passes, but poverty perpetuates from generation to generation one of the most difficult occupations in the world: what human mules from Kawah-Ijena do.
Singapore is looking for children to save the economy
Singaporeans blame career, stress, and housing and education prices for the absence of children.
“Singapore’s population needs to grow.”
I'm a patriot's husband, you're my patriot's wife, let's do our civic duty and create a life!
It may seem unbelievable that these lines are part of a mint cake ad, but despite this — or perhaps because of it — this video became a hit on YouTube in Singapore earlier this year.
These phrases are part of a rap that uses local sayings like "Let's put a bao (bride) in the stove" to make fun of Singapore's birth rate.
The advertising agency that made this video, BBH, cherishes the hope that with the help of advertising they will be able to draw attention to this problem in an entertaining way.
His creative director, Douglas Hamilton, says he wanted to use the power of music to get people to do “their national duty.”
This thing is purely for the internet, so we had to make it fun and funny.
This is the main problem in the country.
We are the worst in the world in reproducing our kind, so we felt that this is the topic we should touch on.
We knew that the government was trying to do a lot, such as launching perfumes with pheromones or organizing quick-dating parties.
Many of these ideas may have been creative, but they didn’t necessarily work.
So we thought, why don't we do the most creative thing we can to solve this problem, namely, rap?
1.2 children
Who doesn’t take this lightly is the government of Singapore.
It spends $1,300 a year on policies to encourage citizens to have more children.
The state package for married couples and parents provides up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave, and provides tax breaks.
All of this has low efficiency.
Singapore is a wealthy and high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for its conservative leadership and its strict public control.
Singapore ' s fertility rate, according to its national population authority, is currently at 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was below 2 – known as a replacement percentage – was in 1976.
So why don’t Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Min, director of the Department of Marriage and Family Policy at the National Population Administration, says the reason is “improved education” and “a wider range of career opportunities.”
“This has allowed people to have a wider range of choices in terms of life goals and priorities beyond getting married and starting a family,” she explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to the increase in the number of bachelors and the postponement of marriages and childbirths, resulting in lower birth rates in Singapore.
Meanwhile, immigration policies, which aim to dramatically increase immigration to counteract declining populations, are causing outrage among the local population.
There are websites in Singapore where scarcely hidden xenophobia thrives against many new immigrants, especially Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and unwilling to integrate.
The rise in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons Singapore’s ruling party scored the worst election result since independence last year.
After the election, there was an attempt to solve the problem, through quotas and higher taxes for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the fall in fertility has a known impact on the nation’s economic growth, tax revenues, medical expenses, and immigration policies, Singapore’s example is also starting to have some unexpected consequences.
The government is making efforts not to build so many small dwellings.
For example, it began to affect the real estate sector.
The urban development guide has shifted to controlling the number of small apartments known as “shoe boxes” that can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments with an area of 46 square meters sell very well.
However, there is an opinion that they can promote a single lifestyle and deprive the incentive of developers who want to build large family housing.
But Lim Yoo Sun, CEO of homebuilder EL Developers, says their “shoe boxes” sell much faster than the more spacious ones.
They are more popular in the sense that such apartments are sold out for several days, even weeks, faster than larger apartments.
As a result, our cash flow increases.
However, he acknowledges that the new norms provide clearer guidelines for developers who were previously hampered if they wanted to offer too many small apartments in the project.
Too overstretched
Singapore is a city-state.
While these new rules may be a step towards increasing national fertility, after talking to Singaporeans who work in the center’s financial quarter, they don’t seem to have much effect.
“People are very stressed out, housing is expensive, as is education, and because of this, many people put it off,” says the young manager.
Other people may have children.
“But it’s important for me to have my own money and time,” says another young man, 20 years old.
Men and women cite their careers, stress, and housing and education prices as reasons that prevent them from having children.
So, no matter how much the government tries to encourage its citizens to have children, the Singaporeans have the final say in terms of procreation.
Personal in offline - personal in online
Confidentiality.
According to the dictionary of the Royal Academy of Spanish, it is a property of private or "the sphere of private life, which they have the right to protect against any interference".
What is personal for a minor under the age of 16?
How does he apply this definition in his daily life and in social media?
Does he understand the dangers he faces when discussing situations on the Internet that he would certainly not share offline?
elPeriódico interviewed five boys between the ages of 10 and 15, frequent users of the network.
In four cases, they associated the term with “something very mine,” in a personal way, and “password and username,” when they applied it to social media.
“My biggest secrets I wouldn’t upload to a post,” Jorge, 10, says as he tries to explain the importance of personal on sites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he’s had accounts for two years.
"These are very secret secrets, my mother may know them, but not the whole world," he said.
On FB I upload beautiful pictures or pictures from games.
I also have fun with my friends.
“I wouldn’t share a photo that wasn’t mine, or someone who was acting stupid,” he says.
The boy realizes that it is bad to publish obscene photos of naked people, crimes or write offensive or angry comments.
Jorge says he knows 35 friends he has on FB and nine of his Twitter followers.
Most of them are relatives.
The mother knows she has a password to one of the accounts.
I started Twitter to express myself and write interesting tweets.
“I don’t know if they’re answering me, I’m just uploading them,” he adds.
“Social media is fun, I can talk to distant relatives or my friends quickly,” he says.
Without hesitation, he answers that he would never accept a request from a stranger.
I wouldn't consider someone who would recommend him to a stranger.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
This teenager has open accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, and in the latter admits that he does not know the 20 people added to his list of friends.
“It doesn’t scare me because we have something in common, like music,” he says.
According to the boy, no one rubbed into his trust and did not ask for his home address or phone number.
“If I’m pressured or demanded, I’ll just delete them from my account,” he admits.
Jose became a follower of Ask after reading the recommendation on Twitter.
The boy is not alien to the experience of what is known today as cybermobbing.
A friend of mine was blackmailed on a social network.
He was threatened and extorted money.
“He never knew who it was,” he said.
The victim, according to Jose, did not delete the account.
"Just turned on confidentiality."
He then explains the sequence of steps to set up an account in a secure way.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would upload photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yes, I would do it if I didn’t like the person or if I wanted to.
“Although I know it’s cybermobbing,” he confirms.
Key Issues
Marielos Porras, an English teacher and education and training specialist, believes that in order to guide children and adolescents, it is necessary to understand that the purpose of social networks is to inform.
“The Internet has emerged as a means of finding information, but with the advent of these sites, the rules of the game have changed,” she said.
Porras points out that academic Mark Prensky, a master of pedagogy at Yale University and author of Digital Aborigines and Immigrants, invented these terms to explain the phenomenon.
Digital Aborigines are they, the children and young people who were born in the age of technology.
“We’re digital immigrants who have to teach them while we’re still learning,” she says.
He explains that this topic is complex, “because we ask them to have a certain criterion of what can or cannot be distributed, published or spoken at an age where maturity is not enough for it.”
“Also to make them selective, while the most important thing for them is to be popular, to have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences,” she adds.
According to the expert, the most effective way to show what privacy is for children and adolescents is to ask questions that make them think.
“Telling them not to do it is useless,” she adds.
Then Porras lists some options: there are things you wouldn’t tell a stranger, so why do you do it online?
Or would you like it if they published a photo of you like the one you posted about your friend?
Do you know what others are posting about you?
When you sign party photos, do you ask permission from other people to mark them?
And one more thing, does everyone need to know what you're doing at every moment?
Another point is to let them know that they need to behave online in the same way they do offline.
The same rules.
“Outside of the Internet, a person behaves with respect, responsibility and other principles, so should social media,” she argues.
Vigilance
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, professor of primary education and education consultant, explains the need for heads of families to read social media policies in good faith.
Understanding each of the points, they have good reason to talk to children about the prerequisites for opening an online account.
“For example, the age and what is allowed to be distributed or published,” he says.
According to Gaurdi, the key question is to remind children of the lesson “do not talk to strangers”.
UNASUR summit ends without the release of the Lima Declaration
The sixth presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without the promulgation of the Lima Declaration, announced earlier and theoretically signed by seven obligatory participants.
Efe repeatedly attempted to gain access to the document signed at the sixth regular meeting of the Heads of State and Government of UNASUR, but sources from the Office and the Presidential Administration indicated on the homepage that it would be handed over after the closure, but then confirmed that at some point it would be published on the Peruvian Government's website.
When asked about the text, they pointed out that the contents were presented by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, during brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information about the Summit has been restricted at all times.
During the day, only a video of the presidential assembly was broadcast in the press room without a sound with the message "closed session, no sound".
The little information that circulated among the reporters was provided by the spokespersons of some UNASUR governments present at the meeting, but not the Peruvian one.
The only document circulated during the day was a list of participating presidents, sparking outrage from hundreds of journalists from various national and international media outlets who asked for more information.
Subsequently, the Peruvian presidential administration sent an e-mail to the media with the summit’s “final declaration”, but this is a statement by Umala, and not an official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit of South American and Arab Countries (ASPA), and at that time, despite the press’s insistence, the so-called Lima Declaration, which had previously been announced, was also not circulated.
On the official ASPA website, you can check that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities endeavoured to ensure transmission systems for all journalists, but limited as much as possible the receipt of information.
The summit also concluded with a joint decision by Chile and Peru to accept the verdict of the Hague court, which will settle the territorial dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Umala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at a regional meeting and ratified that they would abide by the ruling of the International Court of Justice, which begins Monday in The Hague hearing statements from both sides, as part of the charge that Lima has brought against Santiago.
“We will respect and enforce a decision that will clarify the differences we are currently presenting to this international court,” said Umala, next to his Chilean counterpart.
“Chile has been, is and will be a country that respects international law, peaceful resolution of differences, pacts and international tribunals,” Piñera added, welcoming Umala’s handshake against the backdrop of the two countries’ flags.
The confirmation by both presidents that they would obey the International Court of Justice came immediately after Colombia protested this week against the Bogota Pact, under which it recognized submission to the verdicts of that international court following the decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, which it deemed erroneous.
The summit was held in the absence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rousseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chávez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, whose membership in UNASUR has been suspended since 2011 after the impeachment of its former president, Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Umala, was responsible for opening the discussions in the morning and closing the summit just after noon Lima time.
The head of state read the final document, in which he said that 16 agreements were adopted and the directions of action for 31 projects among South American countries were approved, the amount of the proposed investments amounted to $ 17 billion.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the UNASUR countries will take "important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which we are expanding the agreements on the place of residence".
He said that actions are being taken to improve “cooperation in the fight against citizens’ insecurity and against organized transnational crime, actions to increase the availability of medicines, inexpensive access to the Internet in all corners of South America and taking into account the combined and effective risk of natural disasters.”
As Europe is in crisis, “the economic union (of Latin America) should not have a triumphant basis, but should serve to expand our productive base and anticipate a better future for our cities,” Umala added.
“We have decided to give privileges to a group of 31 landmark projects that will improve connectivity in South America, especially in rural and border areas... uniting our countries and forming new economic schemes,” the Peruvian president said in a statement.
Among those projects, he mentioned that five were Peru-bound and bounded by transverse axes on its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two were aimed at a greater link with Ecuador, but he did not provide more details.
The final document also touched upon the political situation in Paraguay.
We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve to rejoin the Union of South American Nations, from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, to be united, and to have good relations between neighbours, was another theme highlighted at the summit.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos, before embarking on a regional meeting, said he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico City to hold respectful talks on the maritime dispute as a result of an international court verdict challenged by Bogotá.
“The day after tomorrow (Saturday) I may meet with President Daniel Ortega,” Santos said.
“We will review all these ways, they are not mutually exclusive, including the pact with Nicaragua will require discussion with Nicaragua,” he said.
“With President Ortega, I hope I can tell him that we will deal with this in the most civilized and respectful way possible,” Santos said.
Santos and Ortega will meet in Mexico City on Saturday, where they are scheduled to attend the inauguration of the country's new president, Enrique Peña Nieto.
At the summit, the bloc’s defense ministers met in advance to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which aims to strengthen dialogue and unanimity on the issue of protecting the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay form UNASUR, although the latter’s participation has been suspended.
Peru holds the interim presidency of the regional bloc.
"South America must learn from Europe on the integration of citizenship": Rafael Correa
Ecuador’s president, Rafael Correa, confirmed today that the creation of a common citizenship is a goal in which “South America, in this case, yes, should learn from Europe.”
Correa, who took part in the 6th presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) held in Lima, told Peru's state television that Europeans "killed each other during World War II" and other clashes, "but now they are practically the same homeland."
He defended, in this context, a project to establish South American citizenship, which is endorsed by the UNASUR member countries.
“We need to achieve free movement of citizens and workers in any South American country, as is already the case with members of the Andean Community, but there are still reactionary sectors that want to take us back in time,” he warned.
The Ecuadorian President has also shown himself a supporter of the renewed Organization of American States (OAS) on the premise of reducing the influence of the Anglo-Saxon States and taking into account those who have signed the San Jose Pact on human rights.
Those who give lectures never make any commitments, and we South Americans, on the contrary, sign everything.
"It is inexplicable that the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights is in Washington and is funded by the United States," he said, hinting at Ecuador's grant of political asylum to WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange.
Correa assured that he did not regret this decision, because with it he did not betray his principles, but respected his “deep values of democracy and human rights”.
He added that at one time “there were certain suspicions that Assange would be extradited to a third country and the process would not be followed.”
He also criticized Swedish justice for demanding to come to his territory for questioning on the alleged sexual offence, while “Swedish law itself considers it possible to carry it out by videoconference, which could be done from the Ecuadorian embassy in London”.
Correa confirmed that there is a risk of deteriorating Assange’s physical and mental health.
“I haven’t spoken to him since he arrived at our embassy, but the ambassador told me he had a small pulmonary problem, nothing serious,” he said.
What it really is, is the danger of deteriorating his physical and mental health due to imprisonment in a small space without the ability to do exercises in the air.
“It affects the health of any person,” he added.
Correa pointed out that a solution to the asylum issue granted to Assange since June at the Ecuadorean embassy in London through the provision of a security guarantee that would allow him to travel to Ecuador is in the hands of the UK, Sweden and the European judiciary, and stressed that there have been negotiations in London to find a solution to the problem of the imprisonment of the founder of WikiLeaks.
We are not negotiating on human rights, we do not use this word in this case, but there have been constant discussions.
"The solution to this problem is in the hands of the UK, Sweden and the European judiciary, because Assange's lawyer, Baltasar Garzón, is conducting a number of trials in various European bodies," he said.
He said: “If the UK gives us a guarantee of immunity tomorrow, it will be over.”
And if Sweden, as its legislation perfectly allows it and as it has done on other occasions, interrogates Mr. Assange at the Ecuadorian embassy in London or interrogates him via Skype, tomorrow the problem will be exhausted.
Correa took the opportunity to show himself as a defender of freedom of the press and stressed that he does not tolerate “mediumliness, bad faith and lies that distort freedom of expression”.
“The main enemies of press freedom are not corrupt political villains, but bad journalists who support profit, blackmail and extortion,” he said.
In this regard, he was pleased that neither these journalists, “neither the bankers nor the bourgeois hegemonic countries dominate Ecuador,” and added that being re-elected “will deepen the revolution to continue development in the right direction.”
Correa also supported the decision to keep Paraguay’s veto in UNASUR at least until the next election, arguing that the organization “should be firm and not tolerate opportunism and support for coups under the guise of legality” because in fact “it has destroyed the legitimacy of Paraguayan democracy”.
The Ecuadorian president also considered the desire of his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, to hold talks with Nicaragua on the maritime borders between the two countries as a result of the decision of the International Court of Justice of The Hague, which proved in favor of Nicaraguan maritime sovereignty, to be “fully justified”.
This decision is not being respected at the moment.
This is a problem between South American and Central American countries.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome by the desire to go together.
We need to process them together to overcome them and continue to move forward.
He also expressed hope for a good conclusion to the dispute over the maritime borders, which is in the same court of Peru and Chile, and said that “it is right for Latin America to appeal to the international authorities, if the two countries undertake to make a decision, no matter how difficult it may be”.
Regarding the possibility of running as a candidate in the upcoming presidential elections in Ecuador to run for a third consecutive term, he pointed out that he is considering this possibility "with great optimism and joy, although sometimes it is quite difficult".
Correa has said that if he loses the election in February 2013, he will withdraw from public life.
Personally, I have never been interested in power, but in such unjust situations as in Ecuador, socio-economic poverty can only be corrected by political power.
“My political movement felt that I was the one who guaranteed this probable victory, so I have to acknowledge that responsibility,” he said.
If I win, it would be my last term as president, and then we're out of public life.
If we lose, it's the same.
“This is a decision,” he confirmed.
Correa also mentioned a new course of treatment for Venezuelan President Hugo Chávez in Cuba.
I just spoke with Venezuelan Vice President Nicolás Maduro, who told me that he had gone for treatment that had already been planned, routine, and that he was expected to miss the campaign to return to Cuba.
“This does not mean that President Chávez’s health is deteriorating,” he said.
The Ecuadorian head of state took part today in Lima in the VI Summit of Heads of State and Government of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR), which concluded with calls for greater regional integration to support progress, equality and security.
AIDS mortality today is the result of late diagnosis
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was announced that his AIDS test had come back positive.
“I feel like I’ve been stunned,” he recalls that difficult moment, despite all the tact of the doctor.
The young man hid it from his family.
Deciding to cope with the disease on his own, he wanted to learn as much about it as possible. And his efforts were realized - he already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
Fabrizio is one of the "oldest" patients in the HIV department of the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), where he arrived in 1994, having overcome many obstacles.
He has been diagnosed with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years. In the early 1990s, it would have been hard to believe that there were too few treatment options, too little knowledge about the disease, too much bias towards patients.
Even the director of the clinic of the Mexican Institute of social protection did not want to say goodbye to him, “because he had a cut”.
In other words, in those days, having AIDS was a verdict.
It is now possible to survive this syndrome and do so without compromising the quality of life.
However, unaware of their illness, still many people come when the virus has already caused damage, "depleted" their immune system and they suffer from opportunistic infections.
31 years after the emergence of AIDS in the world, at least after the first reported cases, "the great achievement at the moment is that the survival of a patient who starts treatment on time, and the survival of the general population is exactly the same," said the head of the HIV department of HCG, Jaime Andrade Villanueva.
HIV/AIDS expert Andrade Villanueva explained that since 2008, scientists have come to the conclusion that AIDS is not a sentence, but the duration and quality of life depends on the degree of damage to the immune system that patients have at the beginning of the diagnosis, with the best life expectancy for those who do not use drugs.
Simply put, the above means that someone who is diagnosed with HIV positive at the age of 25, according to these terms, "by maintaining control, will be able to live without problems up to 75 years," he explained.
To assess this progress, it should be remembered that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Although mortality has declined significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people dying from AIDS has fallen from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (UNAIDS annual report), and it is also true that since the onset of AIDS, 60 percent of patients in the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and 187 deaths have been reported by May this year; however, there has been widespread access to antiretroviral drugs since 2005.
Why are there still fatalities?
Personally, I don't think the problem is access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's how things are at our hospital.
For at least the last 12 years we have not had a shortage of medicines, the problem is that patients come very late because they are not aware of their infected condition, that is, in the late stages of the disease.
“Nine out of ten patients come when they already have some opportunistic infection; what needs to be done to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to diagnose at an earlier stage, and therefore it is necessary to provide samples for detection on a massive scale, for all people who ask.”
In his proposal, experts and officials of the State Council for the Prevention of AIDS in Jalisco (COESIDA) agree, as well as the patients themselves, like Fabricio, who applied for a test in a private laboratory, prompted only by the fact that his friend did it and, despite his young age, he was ill.
Things change when you know you have AIDS.
Some people think they’re going to die and don’t want to know.
"If I'm going to die anyway, I'd rather get pumped three times a week," they say. But not in my case.
There are positive changes, I eat well, do exercise, take medication.
To date, his parents only know that he has had cancer.
I live a normal life like any other.
“I work, I have a lot of classes, I travel, I have an active sex life, but with mutual responsibility, I take care of myself and the other person,” Fabrizio, who agreed to share his personal life with MILENIO JALISCO, said in a statement.
Let them be checked if there was a risk of infection, let them know as soon as possible if they are HIV positive, so it is better, and if they already have a diagnosis, let them know that they can live like any other person, being responsible.
This report summarizes the theme of the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There is a big gap between health care programs and the common citizen, says Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has tackled the HIV-related issue.
The biggest is prevention.
In places dedicated to this task, “in fact, the distribution of condoms has increased, before we were given one or two, now we are given packets of a hundred, and that’s very good, but it turns out that there are those who still do not have access to a condom,” he said.
Adolescents are among the most vulnerable to new infections.
"Why do you need them?" is a popular question, with venom and condemnation, from social workers, school counselors, pharmacy workers and health workers who do not want to hear teenagers, the propagandist assured.
I propose to change this inefficient distribution; so that condoms are not only behind the counters and that hundreds of them are in vending machines in public toilets in places frequented by young people.
This is not encouragement of debauchery.
It's not about paying for beer and a motel, Governor Emilio González said when asked if condoms could be distributed under his leadership.
“It’s not sexuality, it’s best to make condoms available to those who already practice sexual activity,” he said.
Key data in Jalisco
There were 13,435 total cases (12,158 of AIDS and 1,317 of HIV).
The state ranks 4th in the national ranking for new and total AIDS cases and 13th for HIV.
92% of infections are related to the sexual pathway, 6% through the blood and 2% to the perinatal pathway.
It is estimated that 50,000 people can live with HIV, as there are 4 to 5 people for one reported case who do not know about it.
Given the ratification by the United States Court of Appeal of a decision annulling the restructuring of the Vitro Group’s debt achieved through competitive proceedings in Mexico, the scenario sets a fatal precedent for any national company with branches in a neighboring country that has solvency problems.
It seems that the procedures in support of the survival of firms, which are allowed by Mexican laws, are not valid in the country of stripes and stars, contrary to international agreements.
In practical terms, the approval of Judge Harlene Hale’s decision on June 15 in the bankruptcy court of the Northern District of Texas leaves Mexican firms defenseless in the face of the possibility of seizure of their property on the other side of the Rio Grande.
The ruling, however, opens the door to a leading glass manufacturer in Mexico to appeal to the United States Supreme Court, citing three inconsistencies as evidence.
As an introduction, while the judge of the case notes that creditors should be governed by the U.S. Bankruptcy Code, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, located in New Orleans, says the main proceedings concern competitive proceedings pending in Mexico.
The first paragraph implies the cancellation of international judicial cooperation in cases of insolvency of transnational enterprises.
In fact, for this purpose, the UN Model Law on the Unification of International Trade Law was created, designating the American Institute of Law as an arbitrator.
Secondly, the verdict establishes that without intercompany voting, the critically recognised debts of the Vitro branches to the parent company would not have reached the majority required to approve the restructuring.
However, this possibility is recognized by Mexican law.
In fact, Vitro was not the first time this scheme was adopted.
There are half a dozen examples, among them Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose intercompany debts are guaranteed by the Federal Institute for Competitive Proceedings.
It is also true that subtracting the votes of the branches, the creditors of Vitro, who fought against it in the courts of the United States, namely the "vultures" funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot International and Liverpool Limited, would not have reached the majority.
The vote would be 45 per cent against 37.
These data are omitted by the Court of Appeal.
On the other hand, he blames Vitro for the difficult situation that it has faced since 2008, affected by the serious economic crisis that has overtaken the United States, hitting the country.
So far, the González Sáda family firm will appeal the decision to the Court of Appeal itself, so that the vote reaches its plenary, that is, five judges, in view of the fact that only three voted.
