Hector "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball was my life"
The avid basketball traveler Hector "Hetin" Reyes has been associated with this sport for more than 60 years and, thanks to him, traveled around the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico remember as many basketball stories as Hector "Hetin" Reyes.
And after all, before a brain hemorrhage chained him to a wheelchair in 2008, Reyes had been immersed in the sport for more than 60 years, as a minor player, a Major League Baseball player, commissioner and head of BSN with the Bayamon Cowboys, and president of the Basketball Federation.
“I have played many roles in basketball throughout my life, including several at the same time as when I was president of BSN, president of the National Team and president of the federation in the 1990s,” Reyes recalls during Primera Hora’s visit to his home in Bayamon, where he lives with Isabel, his faithful wife, for more than 50 years.
“Basketball was my life.
Reyes does not exaggerate making this claim.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photographs and memorabilia collected over his long journey, testify to this.
Bayamonet in the Heart
With the greatest emotion he keeps those who remember his way through the Cowboys, from the mid-50s as a player until 1982, when he turned 15 years old as a co-agent or contract agent.
“These were my best years, which I enjoyed the most because I had the opportunity to be part of eight Cowboy Championships since 1967, as an agent, co-agent or manager.
There have been many years of joy, including five championships from 1971 to 1975.
And then I said goodbye to one in 1981, the year Jerome Minsey made his debut on BSN.
From that moment on, Cuco Ortiz, who was a great administrator, took over,” Reyes said.
I remember Jean Bartov, who was on his way here and was at the University of Alabama in Birmingham, telling me, "I have a very strong player for you, 6'7".
"Do you want?"
And that was the start of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico had.
Bartov then recommended sniper Raymond Gauss, who obtained citizenship and became one of our best bombers.
I remember saying that if Mincy had brought the championship to Bayamón, Gauss would have helped win another one.
I enjoyed the championship Cowboys with Gauss, but at a distance, because by 1988 he was already the head of the federation.
By that time, I preferred to enjoy his achievements and Mincy’s achievements in the national team.
I remember the first time we won against the United States during the Olympic qualifying tournament in Mexico in 1989.
Then came the 1990 World Cup, where we took fourth place and it should have been bronze, if not for that Canadian referee who forced us to overplay the final game, Reyes said.
Is that team from the 1990 World Cup the best team you’ve ever seen?
She is among the best, as well as the one that won the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite was from the 1991 Pan American Games in Cuba, when we won gold and beat the U.S. national team, which was quite similar to the one that won bronze at the World Cup.
That team not only again played Mincy, Gauss, Ramón Rivas, Fico López and Piculina (Ortiz), but also the young (Javier) 'Toñito' Colon and James Carter, brothers Leon (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario 'Quijote' Morales, who was unable to participate in 90 due to injury.
The team, which may not have been the best in terms of personnel, but brought us a gold medal and great joy, was the team of the 1995 Olympic qualifying tournament in Neuquén, Argentina.
With role-players like Canito Nieves, Pablo Alicea and young Rolando Hurruitner in exchange for players temporarily suspended for a mess in the Pan American Championship of Mar del Plata, we won gold against all predictions.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
Without a doubt, it was Pikulin Ortiz.
His performance in international tournaments is impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico dominated this level as Pikulin did.
This is without taking into account his career in the different leagues in which he played.
Who was the best Puerto Rican leader?
That's a very difficult question.
We had a very good youngster, including Julio Toro, Flora Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
From a young age, I really like Leo Arilla's work.
What do you consider to be your greatest achievement in the federation?
Participation in the most glorious era of the national team between 1988 and 1995, and that in the early 90s BSN had up to 17 teams per season.
What's left for you to do?
There were things I wanted to implement, for example, regionalization of smaller categories.
For example, for Ponce boys to play only in their area and only against teams from other parts of the island in the national playoffs.
Now the guys travel and play too much, and it’s superfluous.
At least I see the fruits of mandatory certification and coursework for managers, officials and judges.
It gives me pleasure.
What are you doing now?
Most of all, I listen to music, watch music videos of my era on YouTube, enjoy my grandchildren and occasionally go to basketball matches.
And, of course, I enjoy the company of my wife, Isabel, who has always been with me.
Actor Larry Hagman has died.
Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931 in Fort Worth, Texas, became world-famous for his starring role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R.", in the television series "Dallas", in which he portrayed a businessman without principles, evil and manipulative.
Larry Hagman, whose role as oil tycoon J.R. Ewing in the TV series Dallas became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in the new season of Dallas, died Friday evening of complications caused by cancer, according to a family statement provided to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., a Dallas production studio.
“Larry is back in his beloved hometown of Dallas, playing the iconic role he loved the most,” his family said in a statement.
Larry’s family and closest friends were with him in Dallas at the Thanksgiving Fair.
Linda Gray, who played his wife in the original series and the sequel, was next to Hagman when he died at the Dallas hospital, her spokesman Jeffrey Lane said.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, cheerful, affectionate and talented, and I will miss him very much.
"He was an original person and lived a full life," Gray said in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with cirrhosis of the liver in 1992 and admitted to drinking for many years.
In 1995, he was diagnosed with a malignant tumor in the liver and underwent a transplant.
Long before Dallas, Hagman became famous on television for his decent-looking role in the light comedy I Dream of Jeannie, which aired on NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In it, he plays Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life changes when he meets an attractive genie girl played by Barbara Eden and begins to live with her under the same roof.
He was also the main character in two comedies that rarely appeared on the air, The Good Life (NBC, 1971–72) and Here We Go Again (ABC, 1973).
His film work included roles well-received by critics in The Group, Harry and Tonto, and Primary Colors.
But it was his masterful interpretation of the delightfully disgusting J.R. that brought Hagman to the top of fame.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and other characters in its entourage aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The advertising slogan "Who Shot J.R.?", designed to create a buzz around an episode full of emotions in which Hagman's character was almost killed, spawned international discussions and millions of dollars that were risked in bookmakers.
It also helped to attract a record audience to the series at the time.
When the response was given in the November 1980 episode, an average of 41 million TV viewers watched it and turned Dallas into the second most watched entertainment program in history, following the 1983 finale of Mash, which attracted 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law, Christine (played by Mary Crosby), who shot him.
J.R. interrupted her and then threatened to accuse her of prostitution if she didn’t leave town, but others also had reasons to attack him.
Hagman played Ewing as an insatiable corrupt man with a charismatic smile: a dishonest entrepreneur and an unfaithful husband who wanted his alcoholic wife, Sue Ellen (Linda Gray), to be put in treatment.
“I know what should be on J.R.’s gravestone,” Hagman said in 1988.
It must be said, "Here rests the honest citizen J.R. Ewing."
That's the only deal he's lost.
Victoria Princepal, also the heroine of the original series, recalled Hagman on Friday as someone "huge, both on and off the screen."
It is unforgettable and irreplaceable for millions of fans around the world, and in the hearts of each of us who are lucky enough to know and love it.
Ten episodes of the new edition of “Dallas” were shown a few months ago with great success on the channel TNT.
Five episodes of the second season have already been recorded and the sixth was in production, the channel reported.
Warner or TNT have not yet made a statement about what will happen to the series after Hagman’s departure.
